e NWS Cooperative Observer Network. Trends are statistically significant for the summer and fall seasons.',NULL,'1895-01-01 00:00:00','2011-12-31 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'testingtesting',NULL,NULL,NULL),(68,4,'1895-2011 trends in temperature anomaly and precipitation anomaly','1895-2010 trends in temperature anomaly (°F/decade) and precipitation anomaly (inches/decade) based on a new gridded version of the COOP data from the National Climatic Data Center (R. Vose, personal communication, June 06, 2011) for the entire U.S. Great Plains (top), northern Great Plains (middle), and southern Great Plains (bottom), for each season as well as the year as a whole. Only values statistically significant at the 95% confidence level are displayed. Statistical significance of trends was assessed using Kendall’s tau coefficient. The test using tau is a non-parametric hypothesis test.',NULL,'1895-01-01 00:00:00','2011-12-31 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'testingtesting',NULL,NULL,NULL),(69,4,'Time series of an index for the occurrence of heat waves and cold waves','Time series of an index for the occurrence of cold waves defined as 4-day periods that are colder than the threshold for a 1 in 5 year recurrence, for the Great Plains region. Based on data from the National Climatic Data Center for the NWS Cooperative Observer Network and updated from Kunkel et al. (1999). Only stations with less than 10% missing daily temperature data for the period 1895-2010 are used in this analysis. Events are first identified for each individual station by ranking all 4-day period mean temperature values and choosing the lowest non-overlapping N/5 events, where N is the number of years of data for that particular station. Then, event numbers for each year are averaged for all stations in each 1x1° grid box. Finally, a regional average is determined by averaging the values for the individual grid boxes. This regional average is the cold wave index. While there is no overall trend, the number of intense cold wave events has been very low during the last 15 years.',NULL,'1895-01-01 00:00:00','2010-12-31 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'testingtesting',NULL,NULL,NULL),(71,4,'Time series of extreme precipitation','Time series of extreme precipitation index for the occurrence of 1-day, 1 in 5 year extreme precipitation, for the Great Plains region. Based on data from the National Climatic Data Center for the NWS Cooperative Observer Network and updated from Kunkel et al. (2003). Only stations with less than 10% missing daily precipitation data for the period 1895-2010 are used in this analysis. Events are first identified for each individual station by ranking all daily precipitation values and choosing the top N/5 events, where N is the number of years of data for that particular station. Then, event numbers for each year are averaged for all stations in each 1x1° grid box. Finally, a regional average is determined by averaging the values for the individual grid boxes. This regional average is the extreme precipitation index. The overall trend is not statistically significant.',NULL,'1895-01-01 00:00:00','2010-12-31 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'testingtesting',NULL,NULL,NULL),(72,4,'Time series of growing season anomalies','Growing season anomalies shown as number of days per year. Length of the growing season is defined as the period between the last occurrence of 32°F in the spring and first occurrence of 32°F in the fall. Red line is a linear fit. Based on data from the National Climatic Data Center for the NWS Cooperative Observer Network and updated from Kunkel et al. (2004). Only stations with less than 10% missing daily temperature data for the period 1895-2010 are used in this analysis. Freeze events are first identified for each individual station. Then, event dates for each year are averaged for 1x1° grid boxes. Finally, a regional average is determined by averaging the values for the individual grid boxes. There has been an increase in growing sea