mulate general increases with the largest changes in the north. ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(143,3,'NARCCAP, SRES A2, MAXIMUM CONSECUTIVE NUMBER OF DAYS PRECIP < 3MM','Simulated difference in the mean annual maximum number of consecutive days with precipitation of less than 0.1 inches/3 mm for the Northeast region, for the 2041-2070 time period with respect to the reference period of 1980-2000 (top). Color only (category 1) indicates that less than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in the number of consecutive days. Color with stippling (category 3) indicates that more than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in the number of consecutive days, and more than 67% agree on the sign of the change (see text). Mean annual maximum number of consecutive days with precipitation of less than 0.1 inches/3 mm for the 1980-2000 reference period (bottom left). Simulated mean annual maximum number of consecutive days with precipitation of less than 0.1 inches/3 mm for the 2041-2070 future time period (bottom right). These fields are multi-model means from 8 NARCCAP regional climate simulations for the high (A2) emissions scenario. The models simulate little change over the majority of the region, with slight decreases in the south.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(144,3,'NARCCAP summary statistics (precipitation)','Multi-model means and standard deviations of the simulated mean annual change in select precipitation variables from 9 NARCCAP simulations for the Northeast region. Multi-model means from the 11 Daily_CMIP3 simulations are also shown for comparison. Analyses are for the 2041-2070 time period with respect to the reference period of 1971-2000, for the high (A2) emissions scenario.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(145,3,'Observed decadal mean annual temperature change ','Observed decadal mean annual temperature change (deviations from the 1901-1960 average, °F) for the Northeast U.S. (black line). Based on a new gridded data set from NCDC for the NWS Cooperative Observer Network (R. Vose, personal communication, June 06, 2011). Gray lines indicate the 20th and 21st century simulations from 15 CMIP3 models, for the high (A2) emissions scenario. The observed rate of warming is within the envelope of model simulations.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(146,3,'Observed decadal mean seasonal temperature change','Observed decadal mean temperature change (deviations from the 1901-1960 average, °F) for the Northeast U.S. for winter (top left, blue line), spring (top right, green line), summer (bottom left red line), and fall (bottom right, orange line). Based on a new gridded data set from NCDC for the NWS Cooperative Observer Network (R. Vose, personal communication, June 06, 2011). Gray lines indicate 20th and 21st century simulations from 15 CMIP3 models, for the high (A2) emissions scenario. The observed amount of 20th century warming is generally within the envelope of model simulations.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(147,3,'Observed decadal mean annual precipitation change','Observed decadal mean annual precipitation change (deviations from the 1901-1960 average, %) for the Northeast U.S. (black line). Based on a new gridded data set from NCDC for the NWS Cooperative Observer Network (R. Vose, personal communication, June 06, 2011). Gray lines indicate the 20th and 21st century simulations from 15 CMIP3 models, for the high (A2) emissions scenario. Observed precipitation variations are within the model simulations.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(148,3,'Observed decadal mean seasonal precipitation change','Observed decadal mean precipitation change (deviations from the 1901-1960 average, %) for the Northeast U.S. for winter (top left, blue line), spring (top right, green line), summer (bottom left red line), and fall (bottom right, orange line). Based on a new gridded data set from NCDC for the NWS Cooperative Observer Network (R. Vose, personal communication, June 06, 2011). Gray lines indicate 20th and 21st century simulations from 15 CMIP3 models, for the high (A2) emissions scenario. Observed seasonal precipitation variations are within model simulations for all seasons.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(149,3,'Time series of mean annual temperature simulated vs observational','Time series of mean annual temperature for the Northeast region from observations (blue) and from all available CMIP3 global climate model simulations (black and grey). Black represents the mean and grey indicates the 5 and 95% limits of the model simulations. Model mean and percentile limits were calculated for each year separately and then smoothed. Results are shown for the low (B1) emissions scenario (left) and the high (A2) emissions scenario (right). A total of 74 simulations of the 20th century were used. For the 21st century, there were 40 simulations for the high emissions scenario and 32 for the low emissions scenario. For each model simulation, the annual temperature values were first transformed into anomalies by subtracting the simulation’s 1901-1960 average from each annual value. Then, the mean bias between model and observations was removed by adding the observed 1901-1960 average to each annual anomaly value from the simulation. For each year, all available model simulations were used to calculate the multi-model mean and the 5th and 95th percentile bounds for that year. Then, the mean and 5th and 95th percentile values were smoothed with a 5-year moving boxcar average.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(150,3,'Model temperature change scatterplot','Simulated decadal mean change in annual temperature (°F) for the Northeast U.S. for each future decadal time period (represented by their approximate midpoints, e.g. 2015 = 2011-2020), with respect to the reference period of 2001-2010. Values are given for all 15 CMIP3 models for the high (A2, top) and low (B1, bottom) emissions scenarios. Large circles depict the multi-model means. Each individual model is represented by a black plus sign (+), or a red x if the value is statistically significant at the 95% confidence level. Blue lines indicate the 10th and 90th percentiles of 30 annual anomaly values from 1981-2010. The model simulated warming by 2015 is not statistically significant but by mid-21st century, all models simulate statistically significant warming.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(151,3,'Model precipitation change scatterplot','Simulated decadal mean change in annual precipitation (%) for the Northeast U.S. for each future decadal time period (represented by their approximate midpoints, e.g. 2015 = 2011-2020), with respect to the reference period of 2001-2010. Values are given for all 15 CMIP3 models for the high (A2, top) and low (B1, bottom) emissions scenarios. Large circles depict the multi-model means. Each individual model is represented by a black plus sign (+), or a red x if the value is statistically significant at the 95% confidence level. Blue lines indicate the 10th and 90th percentiles of the 30 annual anomaly values from 1981-2010. Many models simulate precipitation changes that are not statistically significant out to the end of the 21st century. ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(152,1,'Projected greenhouse gas emissions and atmospheric CO2 concentrations','a) Global greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions (GtCO2-equivalent per year) from 2000 to 2100 for two of the SRES scenarios: A2 (red line) and B1 (blue line). Adapted from IPCC (2007) Fig. 3.1. b) Observed annual mean (black line) and projected atmospheric CO2 concentrations (ppm) for two of the SRES scenarios: A2 (red line) and B1 (blue line). Observations are measurements from the Mauna Loa Observatory, Hawai‘i, from 1958 to 2008. Projections are from two fast carbon cycle models the Bern Model and the Integrated Science Assessment Model (ISAM). Data from IPCC (2012). These graphs show that the CO2 concentrations are comparable under these two scenarios in the early part of the 21st century but diverge greatly by the end of the century.','Greenhouse gas emissions, CO2 concentrations','1958-01-01 00:00:00','2100-12-31 00:00:00','90','-90','180','-180','Global	Observed, simulated	IPCC	Greenhouse gas emissions, CO2 concentrations',NULL,NULL,'2012-03-06 00:00:00'),(153,1,'Average annual temperature','Average (1981-2010) annual temperature (°F) based on National Weather Service Cooperative Observer stations. ',NULL,'1981-01-01 00:00:00','2010-12-31 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(154,1,'Average annual precipitation','Average (1981-2010) annual precipitation (inches) based on National Weather Service Cooperative Observer stations. ',NULL,'1981-01-01 00:00:00','2010-12-31 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(155,1,'Mean annual freezing level','Mean annual freezing level in the center of the Southwest (over Glen Canyon Dam). Red: above period average. Blue: below period average. Black: Ten-year running mean. From the North American Freezing Level Tracker, WRCC, based on Global Reanalysis data.',NULL,'1948-01-01 00:00:00','2010-12-31 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(156,1,'1895-2011 trends in temperature anomaly and precipitation anomaly','1895-2011 trends in temperature anomaly (°F/decade) and precipitation anomaly (inches/decade) based on a new gridded version of the COOP data from the National Climatic Data Center (R. Vose, personal communication, June 06, 2011) for the Southwest U.S., for each season as well as the year as a whole. Only values statistically significant at the 95% confidence level are displayed. Statistical significance of trends was assessed using Kendall’s tau coefficient. The test using tau is a non-parametric hypothesis test. ',NULL,'1895-01-01 00:00:00','2011-12-31 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(157,1,'Temperature Anomalies','Temperature anomaly (deviations from the 1901-1960 average, °F) for annual (black), winter (blue), spring (green), summer (red), and fall (orange), for the Southwest U.S. Based on data from the National Climatic Data Center for the NWS Cooperative Observer Network. Trends are upward and statistically significant annually and for all seasons.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(158,1,'Mean Min/Max Temperature for Southwest United States','Annual mean maximum temperature for the six states, 1895-2010 (top). Annual mean minimum temperature for the six states, 1895-2010 (bottom). Annual values in red, 10-year running means in blue. PRISM data from Westmap.',NULL,'1895-01-01 00:00:00','2010-12-31 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(159,1,'Total Precipitation for Southwest United States','Annual water year (Oct-Sep) precipitation (inches/month) for the six states of the Southwest U.S., 1895/96-2009/10. Annual values in red, 10-year running means in blue. PRISM data from Westmap.',NULL,'1895-01-01 00:00:00','2010-12-31 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(160,1,'Precipitation Anomalies','Precipitation anomaly (deviations from the 1895-2011 average, inches) for annual (black), winter (blue), spring (green), summer (red), and fall (orange), for the Southwest U.S. Based on data from the National Climatic Data Center for the NWS Cooperative Observer Network. Trends are not statistically significant for any season.',NULL,'1895-01-01 00:00:00','2010-12-31 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(161,1,'Time series of cold waves','Time series of an index for the occurrence of cold waves defined as 4-day periods that are colder than the threshold for a 1 in 5 year recurrence, for the Southwest region. Based on data from the National Climatic Data Center for the NWS Cooperative Observer Network and updated from Kunkel et al. (1999). Only stations with less than 10% missing daily temperature data for the period 1895-2010 are used in this analysis. Events are first identified for each individual station by ranking all 4-day period mean temperature values and choosing the lowest non-overlapping N/5 events, where N is the number of years of data for that particular station. Then, event numbers for each year are averaged for all stations in each 1x1° grid box. Finally, a regional average is determined by averaging the values for the individual grid boxes. This regional average is the cold wave index. There is a statistically significant downward trend and the number of intense cold wave events has been low during the last 15 years.',NULL,'1895-01-01 00:00:00','2010-12-31 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(162,1,'Time series of heat waves','Time series of an index for the occurrence of heat waves defined as 4-day periods that are hotter than the threshold for a 1 in 5 year recurrence, for the Southwest region. Based on data from the National Climatic Data Center for the NWS Cooperative Observer Network and updated from Kunkel et al. (1999). Only stations with less than 10% missing daily temperature data for the period 1895-2010 are used in this analysis. Events are first identified for each individual station by ranking all 4-day period mean temperature values and choosing the lowest non-overlapping N/5 events, where N is the number of years of data for that particular station. Then, event numbers for each year are averaged for all stations in each 1x1° grid box. Finally, a regional average is determined by averaging the values for the individual grid boxes. This regional average is the heat wave index. There is a statistically significant upward trend of 9%/decade. The most intense heat waves occurred in the 1930s and 2000s.',NULL,'1895-01-01 00:00:00','2010-12-31 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(163,1,'Time series of extreme precipitation','Time series of extreme precipitation index for the occurrence of 1-day, 1 in 5 year extreme precipitation, for the Southwest region. Based on data from the National Climatic Data Center for the NWS Cooperative Observer Network. Only stations with less than 10% missing daily precipitation data for the period 1895-2010 are used in this analysis. Events are first identified for each individual station by ranking all daily precipitation values and choosing the top N/5 events, where N is the number of years of data for that particular station. Then, event numbers for each year are averaged for all stations in each 1x1° grid box. Finally, a regional average is determined by averaging the values for the individual grid boxes. This regional average is the extreme precipitation index. The overall trend is not statistically significant.',NULL,'1895-01-01 00:00:00','2010-12-31 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(164,1,'Time series of growing season anomalies','Growing season anomalies (reference period 1980-2010) shown as number of days per year. Length of the growing season is defined as the period between the last occurrence of 32°F in the spring and first occurrence of 32°F in the fall. Red line is a linear fit. Based on data from the National Climatic Data Center for the NWS Cooperative Observer Network and updated from Kunkel et al. (2004). Only stations with less than 10% missing daily temperature data for the period 1895-2010 are used in this analysis. Freeze events are first identified for each individual station. Then, event dates for each year are averaged for 1x1° grid boxes. Finally, a regional average is determined by averaging the values for the individual grid boxes. There has been a statistically significant increase in growing season length over the past century.',NULL,'1895-01-01 00:00:00','2010-12-31 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(165,1,'Fluctuation in water-surface altitude of Gilbert Bay (south part), Great Salt Lake, 1847 to present','Great Salt Lake elevation, estimated and observed, from USGS. Taken from www.greatsaltlakeinfo.org',NULL,'1847-01-01 00:00:00','2004-06-15 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(166,1,'Reconstructed Naturalized Colorado River Flow at Lees Ferry Near Page, Arizone','Reconstructed Colorado River flow based on tree ring evidence, from Meko et al (2007) and re-plotted by the Climate Assessment for the Southwest (CLIMAS). Available at www.climas.arizona.edu/feature-articles/february-2009.',NULL,'0800-01-01 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(167,1,'CMIP3 Models Listing','Listing of the 15 models used for the CMIP3 simulations (left column). The 11 models used in the daily statistically-downscaled (Daily_CMIP3) analyses are indicated (right column). For detailed characteristics and documentation of the CMIP3 models, see:\rhttp://www-pcmdi.llnl.gov/ipcc/model_documentation/ipcc_model_documentation.php\r',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(168,1,'NARCCAP Models Listing','Combinations of the 4 GCMs and 6 RCMs that make up the 9 NARCCAP dynamically-downscaled model simulations. For detailed characteristics and documentation of the NARCCAP models, see:\rhttp://www.narccap.ucar.edu/data/model-info.html\r',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(169,1,'CMIP3, MULTI-MODEL MEAN SIMULATION Temperature Difference (F) from 1971-2000','Simulated difference in mean annual temperature (°F) for the Southwest region, for each future time period (2021-2050, 2041-2070, and 2071-2099) with respect to the reference period of 1971-2000. These fields are multi-model means from the 15 CMIP3 global climate simulations for the high (A2) and low (B1) emissions scenarios. Color with stippling (category 3) indicates that more than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in temperature, and more than 67% agree on the sign of the change (see text). Temperature changes increase throughout the 21st century, more rapidly for the high emissions scenario.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(170,1,'NARCCAP, SRES A2, TEMPERATURE CHANGE','Simulated difference in mean annual and seasonal temperature (°F) for the Southwest region, for 2041-2070 with respect to the reference period of 1971-2000. These fields are multi-model means from 9 NARCCAP regional climate simulations for the high (A2) emissions scenario. Note that the color scale is different from that of Fig. 15. Annual temperature changes for the NARCCAP simulations are similar to those for the CMIP3 global models (Fig. 15, middle left panel). Seasonal changes are greatest in summer.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(171,1,'Model mean temperature scatterplot (annual)','Simulated annual mean temperature change (°F) for the Southwest region, for each future time period (2021-2050, 2041-2070, and 2071-2099) with respect to the reference period of 1971-2000. Values are given for all 15 CMIP3 models for the high (SRESA2) and low (SRESB1) emissions scenarios. Also shown for 2041-2070 (high emissions scenario only) are values for the 9 NARCCAP models (NARCCAP), as well as for the 4 GCMs used to drive the NARCCAP simulations (NARCCAP_GCMs). The small plus signs indicate each individual model and the circles depict the multi-model means. The range of model-simulated changes is large compared to the mean differences between A2 and B1 in the early and middle 21st century. By the end of the 21st century, the difference between A2 and B1 is comparable to the range of B1 simulations.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(172,1,'Model mean temperature scatterplot (seasonal)','Simulated seasonal mean temperature change (°F) for the Southwest region, for each future time period (2021-2050, 2041-2070, and 2071-2099) with respect to the reference period of 1971-2000. Values are given for all 15 CMIP3 models for the high (A2) emissions scenario. The small plus signs indicate each individual model and the circles depict the multi-model means. Seasons are indicated as follows: winter (DJF, December-January-February), spring (MAM, March-April-May), summer (JJA, June-July-August), and fall (SON, September-October-November). The range of individual model-simulated changes is large compared to the differences among seasons and comparable to the differences between periods. ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(173,1,'Model mean temperature distribution summary (annual)','Distribution of the simulated annual mean change in temperature (°F) from the 15 CMIP3 models for the Southwest region. The lowest, 25th percentile, median, 75th percentile and highest values are given for the high (A2) and low (B1) emissions scenarios, and for each future time period (2021-2050, 2041-2070, and 2071-2099) with respect to the reference period of 1971-2000.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(174,1,'NARCCAP, SRES A2, ANNUAL NUMBER OF DAYS TMAX > 95F','Simulated difference in the mean annual number of days with a maximum temperature greater than 95°F (TMAX > 95F) for the Southwest region, for the 2041-2070 time period with respect to the reference period of 1980-2000 (top). Color only (category 1) indicates that less than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in the number of days. Color with stippling (category 3) indicates that more than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in the number of days, and more than 67% agree on the sign of the change (see text). Mean annual number of days with TMAX > 95F for the 1980-2000 reference period (bottom left). Simulated mean annual number of days with TMAX > 95F for the 2041-2070 future time period (bottom right). These fields are multi-model means from 8 NARCCAP regional climate simulations for the high (A2) emissions scenario. Note that top and bottom color scales are different. The changes are upward everywhere. Increases are smallest at high elevations and largest in the far south of the region.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(175,1,'NARCCAP, SRES A2, ANNUAL NUMBER OF DAYS TMIN < 10F','Simulated difference in the mean annual number of days with a minimum temperature less than 10°F (TMIN < 10F) for the Southwest region, for the 2041-2070 time period with respect to the reference period of 1980-2000 (top). Color only (category 1) indicates that less than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in the number of days. Color with stippling (category 3) indicates that more than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in the number of days, and more than 67% agree on the sign of the change (see text). Mean annual number of days with TMIN < 10F for the 1980-2000 reference period (bottom left). Simulated mean annual number of days with TMIN < 10F for the 2041-2070 future time period (bottom right). These fields are multi-model means from 8 NARCCAP regional climate simulations for the high (A2) emissions scenario. Decreases are largest in the northeast and at high elevations and are smallest in the south and west, in a pattern similar to the present-day climatology.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(176,1,'NARCCAP, SRES A2, ANNUAL NUMBER OF DAYS TMIN < 32F','Simulated difference in the mean annual number of days with a minimum temperature less than 32°F (TMIN < 32F) for the Southwest region, for the 2041-2070 time period with respect to the reference period of 1980-2000 (top). Color with stippling (category 3) indicates that more than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in the number of days, and more than 67% agree on the sign of the change (see text). Mean annual number of days with TMIN < 32F for the 1980-2000 reference period (bottom left). Simulated mean annual number of days with TMIN < 32F for the 2041-2070 future time period (bottom right). These fields are multi-model means from 8 NARCCAP regional climate simulations for the high (A2) emissions scenario. Changes are downward everywhere. Decreases are largest in high elevation areas and smallest along the coast, as well as southern California and Arizona.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(177,1,'NARCCAP, SRES A2, ANNUAL MAXIMUM NUMBER OF CONSECUTIVE DAYS TMAX > 95','Simulated difference in the mean annual maximum number of consecutive days with a maximum temperature greater than 95°F (TMAX > 95F) for the Southwest region, for the 2041-2070 time period with respect to the reference period of 1980-2000 (top). Color only (category 1) indicates that less than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in the number of consecutive days. Color with stippling (category 3) indicates that more than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in the number of consecutive days, and more than 67% agree on the sign of the change (see text). Mean annual maximum number of consecutive days with TMAX > 95F for the 1980-2000 reference period (bottom left). Simulated mean annual maximum number of consecutive days with TMAX > 95F for the 2041-2070 future time period (bottom right). These fields are multi-model means from 8 NARCCAP regional climate simulations for the high (A2) emissions scenario. Note that top and bottom color scales are different. Increases are largest in the south and smallest in areas of high elevation, with a pattern similar to the present-day climatology.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(178,1,'NARCCAP summary statistics (temperature)','Multi-model means and standard deviations of the simulated annual mean change in select temperature variables from 9 NARCCAP simulations for the Southwest region. Multi-model means from the 11 Daily_CMIP3 simulations are also shown for comparison. Analyses are for the 2041-2070 time period with respect to the reference period of 1971-2000, for the high (A2) emissions scenario.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(179,1,'NARCCAP, SRES A2, LENGTH OF FROST-FREE SEASON','Simulated difference in the mean annual length of the frost-free season for the Southwest region, for the 2041-2070 time period with respect to the reference period of 1980-2000 (top). Color with stippling (category 3) indicates that more than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in in the length of the frost-free season, and more than 67% agree on the sign of the change (see text). Annual mean length of the frost-free season for the 1980-2000 reference period (bottom left). Simulated mean annual length of the frost-free season for the 2041-2070 future time period (bottom right). These fields are multi-model means from 8 NARCCAP regional climate simulations for the high (A2) emissions scenario. Note that top and bottom color scales are different. The length of the frost-freeze season is simulated to increase throughout the region, with the greatest changes in the west.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(180,1,'NARCCAP, SRES A2, ANNUAL TOTAL COOLING DEGREE DAYS','Simulated difference in the mean annual number of cooling degree days for the Southwest region, for the 2041-2070 time period with respect to the reference period of 1980-2000 (top). Color with stippling (category 3) indicates that more than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in the number of cooling degree days, and more than 67% agree on the sign of the change (see text). Mean annual number of cooling degree days for the 1980-2000 reference period (bottom left). Simulated mean annual number of cooling degree days for the 2041-2070 future time period (bottom right). These fields are multi-model means from 8 NARCCAP regional climate simulations for the high (A2) emissions scenario. Note that top and bottom color scales are different. There are increases everywhere with the changes becoming larger from north to south.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(181,1,'NARCCAP, SRES A2, ANNUAL TOTAL HEATING DEGREE DAYS','Simulated difference in the mean annual number of heating degree days for the Southwest region, for the 2041-2070 time period with respect to the reference period of 1980-2000 (top). Color with stippling (category 3) indicates that more than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in the number of heating degree days, and more than 67% agree on the sign of the change (see text). Mean annual number of heating degree days for the 1980-2000 reference period (bottom left). Simulated mean annual number of heating degree days for the 2041-2070 future time period (bottom right). These fields are multi-model means from 8 NARCCAP regional climate simulations for the high (A2) emissions scenario. There are decreases everywhere with the largest changes in high elevation areas.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(182,1,'CMIP3, MULTI-MODEL MEAN SIMULATION Precipitation Difference (%) from 1971-2000','Simulated difference in mean annual precipitation (%) for the Southwest region, for each future time period (2021-2050, 2041-2070, and 2071-2099) with respect to the reference period of 1971-2000. These projections are multi-model means from the 15 CMIP3 global climate simulations for the high (A2) and low (B1) emissions scenarios. Color only (category 1) indicates that less than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in precipitation. Color with stippling (category 3) indicates that more than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in precipitation, and more than 67% agree on the sign of the change. Whited out areas (category 2) indicate that more than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in precipitation, but less than 67% agree of the sign of the change (see text). Generally, the models simulate increases in the far north, but decreases in the majority of the region.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(183,1,'Model mean precipitation distribution summary (annual)','Distribution of the simulated annual mean change in precipitation (%) from the 15 CMIP3 models for the Southwest region. The lowest, 25th percentile, median, 75th percentile and highest values are given for the high (A2) and low (B1) emissions scenarios, and for each future time period (2021-2050, 2041-2070, and 2071-2099) with respect to the reference period of 1971-2000. Also shown are values from the distribution of the 9 NARCCAP models (NARCCAP) for 2041-2070, A2 only.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(184,1,'NARCCAP, SRES A2, PRECIPITATION CHANGE','Simulated difference in mean annual and seasonal precipitation (%) for the Southwest region, for 2041-2070 with respect to the reference period of 1971-2000. These projections are multi-model means from 9 NARCCAP regional climate simulations for the high (A2) emissions scenario. Note that top and bottom color scales are unique, and different from that of Fig. 26. The annual change is upward in the far north and downward throughout the remainder of the region. Changes are mostly upward in winter, and downward in spring, summer, and fall.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(185,1,'Model mean precipitation distribution summary (seasonal)','Distribution of the simulated seasonal mean change in precipitation (%) from the 15 CMIP3 models for the Southwest region. The lowest, 25th percentile, median, 75th percentile and highest values are given for the high (A2) and low (B1) emissions scenarios, and for the 2071-2099 time period with respect to the reference period of 1971-2000.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(186,1,'Model mean precipitation scatterplot (annual)','Simulated annual mean precipitation change (%) for the Southwest region, for each future time period (2021-2050, 2041-2070, and 2071-2099) with respect to the reference period of 1971-2000. Values are given for all 15 CMIP3 models for the high (SRESA2) and low (SRESB1) emissions scenarios. Also shown for 2041-2070 (high emissions scenario only) are values for the 9 NARCCAP models (NARCCAP), as well as for the 4 GCMs used to drive the NARCCAP simulations (NARCCAP_GCMs). The small plus signs indicate each individual model and the circles depict the multi-model means. The range of model-simulated changes is very large compared to the mean changes and to differences between the A2 and B1 scenarios.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(187,1,'Model mean precipitation scatterplot (seasonal)','Simulated seasonal mean precipitation change (%) for the Southwest region, for each future time period (2021-2050, 2041-2070, and 2071-2099) with respect to the reference period of 1971-2000. Values are given for all 15 CMIP3 models for the high (A2) emissions scenario. Also shown are values for the 9 NARCCAP models (NARCCAP) for 2041-2070. The small plus signs indicate each individual model and the circles depict the multi-model means. Seasons are indicated as follows: winter (DJF, December-January-February), spring (MAM, March-April-May), summer (JJA, June-July-August), and fall (SON, September-October-November). The range of model-simulated changes is large compared to the mean changes and to differences between the seasons.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(188,1,'NARCCAP, SRES A2, ANNUAL NUMBER OF DAYS PRECIPITATION > 1 INCH','Simulated percentage difference in the mean annual number of days with precipitation of greater than one inch for the Southwest region, for the 2041-2070 time period with respect to the reference period of 1980-2000 (top). Color only (category 1) indicates that less than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in the number of days. Color with stippling (category 3) indicates that more than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in the number of days, and more than 67% agree on the sign of the change. Whited out areas (category 2) indicate that more than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in the number of days, but less than 67% agree of the sign of the change (see text). Mean annual number of days with precipitation of greater than one inch for the 1980-2000 reference period (bottom left). Simulated mean annual number of days with precipitation of greater than one inch for the 2041-2070 future time period (bottom right). These fields are multi-model means from 8 NARCCAP regional climate simulations for the high (A2) emissions scenario. The models simulate decreases in the south and in high elevation areas, with increases across the remainder of the region. ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(189,1,'NARCCAP, SRES A2, MAXIMUM CONSECUTIVE NUMBER OF DAYS PRECIP < 3MM','Simulated difference in the mean annual maximum number of consecutive days with precipitation of less than 0.1 inches/3 mm for the Southwest region, for the 2041-2070 time period with respect to the reference period of 1980-2000 (top). Color only (category 1) indicates that less than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in the number of consecutive days. Color with stippling (category 3) indicates that more than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in the number of consecutive days, and more than 67% agree on the sign of the change (see text). Mean annual maximum number of consecutive days with precipitation of less than 0.1 inches/3 mm for the 1980-2000 reference period (bottom left). Simulated mean annual maximum number of consecutive days with precipitation of less than 0.1 inches/3 mm for the 2041-2070 future time period (bottom right). These fields are multi-model means from 8 NARCCAP regional climate simulations for the high (A2) emissions scenario. The models simulate increases over the majority of the region, with the greatest changes in the south.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(190,1,'NARCCAP summary statistics (precipitation)','Multi-model means and standard deviations of the simulated annual mean change in select precipitation variables from 9 NARCCAP simulations for the Southwest region. Multi-model means from the 11 Daily_CMIP3 simulations are also shown for comparison. Analyses are for the 2041-2070 time period with respect to the reference period of 1971-2000, for the high (A2) emissions scenario.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(191,1,'Observed decadal mean annual temperature change ','Observed decadal mean annual temperature change (deviations from the 1901-1960 average, °F) for the Southwest U.S. (black line). Based on a new gridded data set from NCDC for the NWS Cooperative Observer Network (R. Vose, personal communication, June 06, 2011). Gray lines indicate the 20th and 21st century simulations from 15 CMIP3 models, for the high (A2) emissions scenario. The observed rate of warming is within the envelope of model simulations.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(192,1,'Observed decadal mean seasonal temperature change','Observed decadal mean temperature change (deviations from the 1901-1960 average, °F) for the Southwest U.S. for winter (top left, blue line), spring (top right, green line), summer (bottom left red line), and fall (bottom right, orange line). Based on a new gridded data set from NCDC for the NWS Cooperative Observer Network (R. Vose, personal communication, June 06, 2011). Gray lines indicate 20th and 21st century simulations from 15 CMIP3 models, for the high (A2) emissions scenario. The observed amount of 20th century warming is generally within the envelope of model simulations.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(193,1,'Observed decadal mean annual precipitation change','Observed decadal mean annual precipitation change (deviations from the 1901-1960 average, %) for the Southwest U.S. (black line). Based on a new gridded data set from NCDC for the NWS Cooperative Observer Network (R. Vose, personal communication, June 06, 2011). Gray lines indicate the 20th and 21st century simulations from 15 CMIP3 models, for the high (A2) emissions scenario. Observed precipitation variations are within the model simulations.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(194,1,'Observed decadal mean seasonal precipitation change','Observed decadal mean precipitation change (deviations from the 1901-1960 average, %) for the Southwest U.S. for winter (top left, blue line), spring (top right, green line), summer (bottom left red line), and fall (bottom right, orange line). Based on a new gridded data set from NCDC for the NWS Cooperative Observer Network (R. Vose, personal communication, June 06, 2011). Gray lines indicate 20th and 21st century simulations from 15 CMIP3 models, for the high (A2) emissions scenario. Observed seasonal precipitation variations are within model simulations for all seasons.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(195,1,'Time series of mean annual temperature simulated vs observational','Time series of mean annual temperature for the Southwest region from observations (blue) and from all available CMIP3 global climate model simulations (black and grey). Black represents the mean and grey indicates the 5 and 95% limits of the model simulations. Model mean and percentile limits were calculated for each year separately and then smoothed. Results are shown for the low (B1) emissions scenario (left) and the high (A2) emissions scenario (right). A total of 74 simulations of the 20th century were used. For the 21st century, there were 40 simulations for the high emissions scenario and 32 for the low emissions scenario. For each model simulation, the annual temperature values were first transformed into anomalies by subtracting the simulation’s 1901-1960 average from each annual value. Then, the mean bias between model and observations was removed by adding the observed 1901-1960 average to each annual anomaly value from the simulation. For each year, all available model simulations were used to calculate the multi-model mean and the 5th and 95th percentile bounds for that year. Then, the mean and 5th and 95th percentile values were smoothed with a 5-year moving boxcar average.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(196,1,'Model temperature change scatterplot','Simulated decadal mean change in annual temperature (°F) for the Southwest U.S. for each future decadal time period (represented by their approximate midpoints, e.g. 2015 = 2011-2020), with respect to the reference period of 2001-2010. Values are given for all 15 CMIP3 models for the high (A2, top) and low (B1, bottom) emissions scenarios. Large circles depict the multi-model means. Each individual model is represented by a black plus sign (+), or a red x if the value is statistically significant at the 95% confidence level. Blue lines indicate the 10th and 90th percentiles of 30 annual anomaly values from 1981-2010. The model simulated warming by 2015 is not statistically significant but by mid-21st century, all models simulate statistically significant warming.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(197,1,'Model precipitation change scatterplot','Simulated decadal mean change in annual precipitation (%) for the Southwest U.S. for each future decadal time period (represented by their approximate midpoints, e.g. 2015 = 2011-2020), with respect to the reference period of 2001-2010. Values are given for all 15 CMIP3 models for the high (A2, top) and low (B1, bottom) emissions scenarios. Large circles depict the multi-model means. Each individual model is represented by a black plus sign (+), or a red x if the value is statistically significant at the 95% confidence level. Blue lines indicate the 10th and 90th percentiles of the 30 annual anomaly values from 1981-2010. Many models simulate precipitation changes that are not statistically significant out to the end of the 21st century. ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(198,5,'Projected greenhouse gas emissions and atmospheric CO2 concentrations','a) Global greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions (GtCO2-equivalent per year) from 2000 to 2100 for two of the SRES scenarios: A2 (red line) and B1 (blue line). Adapted from IPCC (2007) Fig. 3.1. b) Observed annual mean (black line) and projected atmospheric CO2 concentrations (ppm) for two of the SRES scenarios: A2 (red line) and B1 (blue line). Observations are measurements from the Mauna Loa Observatory, Hawai‘i, from 1958 to 2008. Projections are from two fast carbon cycle models the Bern Model and the Integrated Science Assessment Model (ISAM). Data from IPCC (2012). These graphs show that the CO2 concentrations are comparable under these two scenarios in the early part of the 21st century but diverge greatly by the end of the century.','Greenhouse gas emissions, CO2 concentrations','1958-01-01 00:00:00','2100-12-31 00:00:00','90','-90','180','-180','Global	Observed, simulated	IPCC	Greenhouse gas emissions, CO2 concentrations',NULL,NULL,'2012-03-06 00:00:00'),(199,5,'Average annual temperature','Average (1981-2010) annual temperature (°F) based on National Weather Service Cooperative Observer stations. These stations are preferentially located at lower elevations and the map does not fully represent the full range of temperature, particularly at higher elevations.',NULL,'1981-01-01 00:00:00','2010-12-31 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(200,5,'Average annual precipitation','Average (1981-2010) annual precipitation (inches) based on National Weather Service Cooperative Observer stations. These stations are preferentially located at lower elevations and the map does not fully represent the full range of precipitation, particularly at higher elevations.',NULL,'1981-01-01 00:00:00','2010-12-31 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(201,5,'1895-2011 trends in temperature anomaly and precipitation anomaly','1895-2011 trends in temperature anomaly (°F/decade) and precipitation anomaly (inches/decade) based on a new gridded version of the COOP data from the National Climatic Data Center (R. Vose, personal communication, June 06, 2011) for the Northwest U.S., for each season as well as the year as a whole. Only values statistically significant at the 95% confidence level are displayed. Statistical significance of trends was assessed using Kendall’s tau coefficient. The test using tau is a non-parametric hypothesis test.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(202,5,'Temperature Anomalies','Temperature anomaly (deviations from the 1901-1960 average, °F) for annual (black), winter (blue), spring (green), summer (red), and fall (orange), for the Northwest U.S. Based on data from the National Climatic Data Center for the NWS Cooperative Observer Network. ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(203,5,'Precipitation Anomalies','Precipitation anomaly (deviations from the 1901-1960 average, inches) for annual (black), winter (blue), spring (green), summer (red), and fall (orange), for the Northwest U.S. Based on data from the National Climatic Data Center for the NWS Cooperative Observer Network.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(204,5,'Time series of cold waves','Time series of an index for the occurrence of cold waves defined as 4-day periods that are colder than the threshold for a 1 in 5 year recurrence, for the Northwest region. Based on data from the National Climatic Data Center for the NWS Cooperative Observer Network and updated from Kunkel et al. (1999). Only stations with less than 10% missing daily temperature data for the period 1895-2010 are used in this analysis. Events are first identified for each individual station by ranking all 4-day period mean temperature values and choosing the lowest non-overlapping N/5 events, where N is the number of years of data for that particular station. Then, event numbers for each year are averaged for all stations in each 1x1° grid box. Finally, a regional average is determined by averaging the values for the individual grid boxes. This regional average is the cold wave index. The overall trend is not statistically significant. The number of intense cold wave events has been low during the last 15 years.',NULL,'1895-01-01 00:00:00','2010-12-31 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(205,5,'Time series of heat waves','Time series of an index for the occurrence of heat waves defined as 4-day periods that are hotter than the threshold for a 1 in 5 year recurrence, for the Northwest region. Based on data from the National Climatic Data Center for the NWS Cooperative Observer Network and updated from Kunkel et al. (1999). Only stations with less than 10% missing daily temperature data for the period 1895-2010 are used in this analysis. Events are first identified for each individual station by ranking all 4-day period mean temperature values and choosing the lowest non-overlapping N/5 events, where N is the number of years of data for that particular station. Then, event numbers for each year are averaged for all stations in each 1x1° grid box. Finally, a regional average is determined by averaging the values for the individual grid boxes. This regional average is the heat wave index. The upward trend is not quite statistically significant. The most intense heat waves occurred in the 1930s and 2000s.',NULL,'1895-01-01 00:00:00','2010-12-31 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(206,5,'Time series of extreme precipitation','Time series of extreme precipitation index for the occurrence of 1-day, 1 in 5 year extreme precipitation, for the Northwest region. Based on data from the National Climatic Data Center for the NWS Cooperative Observer Network. Only stations with less than 10% missing daily precipitation data for the period 1895-2010 are used in this analysis. Events are first identified for each individual station by ranking all daily precipitation values and choosing the top N/5 events, where N is the number of years of data for that particular station. Then, event numbers for each year are averaged for all stations in each 1x1° grid box. Finally, a regional average is determined by averaging the values for the individual grid boxes. This regional average is the extreme precipitation index. The highest number of extreme events occurred in 1996.',NULL,'1895-01-01 00:00:00','2010-12-31 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(207,5,'Time series of growing season anomalies','Growing season anomalies shown as number of days per year. Length of the growing season is defined as the period between the last occurrence of 32°F in the spring and first occurrence of 32°F in the fall. Red line is a linear fit. Based on data from the National Climatic Data Center for the NWS Cooperative Observer Network and updated from Kunkel et al.(2004).',NULL,'1895-01-01 00:00:00','2010-12-31 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(208,5,'CMIP3 Models Listing','Listing of the 15 models used for the CMIP3 simulations (left column). The 11 models used in the daily statistically-downscaled (Daily_CMIP3) analyses are indicated (right column). For detailed characteristics and documentation of the CMIP3 models, see:\rhttp://www-pcmdi.llnl.gov/ipcc/model_documentation/ipcc_model_documentation.php\rListing of the 15 models used for the CMIP3 simulations (left column). The 11 models used in the daily statistically-downscaled (Daily_CMIP3) analyses are indicated (right column). For detailed characteristics and documentation of the CMIP3 models, see:\rhttp://www-pcmdi.llnl.gov/ipcc/model_documentation/ipcc_model_documentation.php\r',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(209,5,'NARCCAP Models Listing','Combinations of the 4 GCMs and 6 RCMs that make up the 9 NARCCAP dynamically-downscaled model simulations. For detailed characteristics and documentation of the NARCCAP models, see:\rhttp://www.narccap.ucar.edu/data/model-info.html\r',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(210,5,'CMIP3, MULTI-MODEL MEAN SIMULATION Temperature Difference (F) from 1971-2000','Simulated difference in mean annual temperature (°F) for the Northwest region, for each future time period (2021-2050, 2041-2070, and 2071-2099) with respect to the reference period of 1971-2000. These fields are multi-model means from the 15 CMIP3 global climate simulations for the high (A2) and low (B1) emissions scenarios. Color with stippling (category 3) indicates that more than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in temperature, and more than 67% agree on the sign of the change (see text). Temperature changes increase throughout the 21st century, more rapidly for the high emissions scenario.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(211,5,'NARCCAP, SRES A2, TEMPERATURE CHANGE','Simulated difference in annual and seasonal mean temperature (°F) for the Northwest region, for 2041-2070 with respect to the reference period of 1971-2000. These fields are multi-model means from 9 NARCCAP regional climate simulations for the high (A2) emissions scenario. Note that the color scale is different from that of Fig. 10. Annual temperature changes for the NARCCAP simulations are similar to those for the CMIP3 global models (Fig. 10, middle left panel), but with greater warming in the southeastern portion of the region. Seasonal warming shows similar patterns in all seasons, with the greatest warming occurring in summer and winter.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(212,5,'Model mean temperature scatterplot (annual)','Simulated annual mean temperature change (°F) for the Northwest region, for each future time period (2021-2050, 2041-2070, and 2071-2099) with respect to the reference period of 1971-2000. Values are given for all 15 CMIP3 models for the high (SRESA2) and low (SRESB1) emissions scenarios. Also shown for 2041-2070 (high emissions scenario only) are values for the 9 NARCCAP models (NARCCAP), as well as for the 4 GCMs used to drive the NARCCAP simulations (NARCCAP_GCMs). The small plus signs indicate each individual model and the circles depict the multi-model means. The range of model-simulated changes is large compared to the mean differences between A2 and B1 in the early and middle 21st century. By the end of the 21st century, the difference between A2 and B1 is comparable to the range of B1 simulations.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(213,5,'Model mean temperature scatterplot (seasonal)','Simulated seasonal temperature change (°F) for the Northwest region, for each future time period (2021-2050, 2041-2070, and 2071-2099) with respect to the reference period of 1971-2000. Values are given for all 15 CMIP3 models for the high (A2) emissions scenario. The small plus signs indicate each individual model and the circles depict the multi-model means. Seasons are indicated as follows: winter (DJF, December-January-February), spring (MAM, March-April-May), summer (JJA, June-July-August), and fall (SON, September-October-November). The range of individual model-simulated changes is large compared to the differences among seasons and comparable to the differences between periods.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(214,5,'Model mean temperature distribution summary (annual)','Distribution of the simulated annual mean change in temperature (°F) from the 15 CMIP3 models for the Northwest region. The lowest, 25th percentile, median, 75th percentile and highest values are given for the high (A2) and low (B1) emissions scenarios, and for each future time period (2021-2050, 2041-2070, and 2071-2099) with respect to the reference period of 1971-2000.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(215,5,'NARCCAP, SRES A2, ANNUAL NUMBER OF DAYS TMAX > 95F','Simulated difference in the mean annual number of days with a maximum temperature greater than 95°F (TMAX > 95F) for the Northwest region, for the 2041-2070 time period with respect to the reference period of 1980-2000 (top). Color only (category 1) indicates that less than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in the number of days. Color with stippling (category 3) indicates that more than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in the number of days, and more than 67% agree on the sign of the change (see text). Mean annual number of days with TMAX > 95F for the 1980-2000 reference period (bottom left). Simulated mean annual number of days with TMAX > 95F for the 2041-2070 future time period (bottom right). These fields are multi-model means from 8 NARCCAP regional climate simulations for the high (A2) emissions scenario. Note that top and bottom color scales are different.. Increases are smallest at high elevations and largest in the southeastern portion of the region.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(216,5,'NARCCAP, SRES A2, ANNUAL NUMBER OF DAYS TMIN < 10F','Simulated difference in the mean annual number of days with a minimum temperature less than 10°F (TMIN < 10F) for the Northwest region, for the 2041-2070 time period with respect to the reference period of 1980-2000 (top). Color only (category 1) indicates that less than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in the number of days. Color with stippling (category 3) indicates that more than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in the number of days, and more than 67% agree on the sign of the change (see text). Mean annual number of days with TMIN < 10F for the 1980-2000 reference period (bottom left). Simulated mean annual number of days with TMIN < 10F for the 2041-2070 future time period (bottom right). These fields are multi-model means from 8 NARCCAP regional climate simulations for the high (A2) emissions scenario. Decreases are largest for inland areas, while coastal regions are simulated to experience almost no change. ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(217,5,'NARCCAP, SRES A2, ANNUAL NUMBER OF DAYS TMIN < 32F','Simulated difference in the mean annual number of days with a minimum temperature less than 32°F (TMIN < 32F) for the Northwest region, for the 2041-2070 time period with respect to the reference period of 1980-2000 (top). Color with stippling (category 3) indicates that more than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in the number of days, and more than 67% agree on the sign of the change (see text). Mean annual number of days with TMIN < 32F for the 1980-2000 reference period (bottom left). Simulated mean annual number of days with TMIN < 32F for the 2041-2070 future time period (bottom right). These fields are multi-model means from 8 NARCCAP regional climate simulations for the high (A2) emissions scenario. Decreases are largest for inland areas, while coastal regions are simulated to experience almost no change. ?',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(218,5,'NARCCAP, SRES A2, ANNUAL MAXIMUM NUMBER OF CONSECUTIVE DAYS TMAX > 95','Simulated difference in the mean annual maximum number of consecutive days with a maximum temperature greater than 95°F (TMAX > 95F) for the Northwest region, for the 2041-2070 time period with respect to the reference period of 1980-2000 (top). Color only (category 1) indicates that less than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in the number of consecutive days. Color with stippling (category 3) indicates that more than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in the number of consecutive days, and more than 67% agree on the sign of the change (see text). Mean annual maximum number of consecutive days with TMAX > 95F for the 1980-2000 reference period (bottom left). Simulated mean annual maximum number of consecutive days with TMAX > 95F for the 2041-2070 future time period (bottom right). These fields are multi-model means from 8 NARCCAP regional climate simulations for the high (A2) emissions scenario. Note that top and bottom color scales are different. Increases are largest in the southeastern portion of the region.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(219,5,'NARCCAP summary statistics (temperature)','Multi-model means and standard deviations of the simulated annual mean change in select temperature variables from 9 NARCCAP simulations for the Northwest region. Multi-model means from the 11 Daily_CMIP3 simulations are also shown for comparison. Analyses are for the 2041-2070 time period with respect to the reference period of 1971-2000, for the high (A2) emissions scenario.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(220,5,'NARCCAP, SRES A2, LENGTH OF FROST-FREE SEASON','Simulated difference in the mean annual length of the frost-free season for the Northwest region, for the 2041-2070 time period with respect to the reference period of 1980-2000 (top). Color with stippling (category 3) indicates that more than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in the length of the frost-free season, and more than 67% agree on the sign of the change (see text). Annual mean length of the frost-free season for the 1980-2000 reference period (bottom left). Simulated mean annual length of the frost-free season for the 2041-2070 future time period (bottom right). These fields are multi-model means from 8 NARCCAP regional climate simulations for the high (A2) emissions scenario. Note that top and bottom color scales are different. Projected increases in the length of the frost-free season are greatest in areas west of the Cascades. ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(221,5,'NARCCAP, SRES A2, ANNUAL TOTAL COOLING DEGREE DAYS','Simulated difference in the mean annual number of cooling degree days for the Northwest region, for the 2041-2070 time period with respect to the reference period of 1980-2000 (top). Color with stippling (category 3) indicates that more than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in the number of cooling degree days, and more than 67% agree on the sign of the change (see text). Mean annual number of cooling degree days for the 1980-2000 reference period (bottom left). Simulated mean annual number of cooling degree days for the 2041-2070 future time period (bottom right). These fields are multi-model means from 8 NARCCAP regional climate simulations for the high (A2) emissions scenario. Note that top and bottom color scales are different. Increases are simulated everywhere, with the greatest increases occurring in southern Idaho and Oregon and southeastern Washington. ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(222,5,'NARCCAP, SRES A2, ANNUAL TOTAL HEATING DEGREE DAYS','Simulated difference in the mean annual number of heating degree days for the Northwest region, for the 2041-2070 time period with respect to the reference period of 1980-2000 (top). Color with stippling (category 3) indicates that more than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in in the number of heating degree days, and more than 67% agree on the sign of the change (see text). Mean annual number of heating degree days for the 1980-2000 reference period (bottom left). Simulated mean annual number of heating degree days for the 2041-2070 future time period (bottom right). These fields are multi-model means from 8 NARCCAP regional climate simulations for the high (A2) emissions scenario. The largest simulated increases are seen in southeastern Idaho, and the smallest increases, along the coast. ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(223,5,'CMIP3, MULTI-MODEL MEAN SIMULATION Precipitation Difference (%) from 1971-2000','Simulated difference in annual mean precipitation (%) for the Northwest region, for each future time period (2021-2050, 2041-2070, and 2071-2099) with respect to the reference period of 1971-2000. These projections are multi-model means from the 15 CMIP3 global climate simulations for the high (A2) and low (B1) emissions scenarios. Color only (category 1) indicates that less than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in precipitation. Color with stippling (category 3) indicates that more than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in precipitation, and more than 67% agree on the sign of the change. Whited out areas (category 2) indicate that more than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in precipitation, but less than 67% agree of the sign of the change (see text). Models simulate increases almost everywhere, and the changes generally become larger moving northward. ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(224,5,'Model mean precipitation distribution summary (annual)','Distribution of the simulated annual mean change in precipitation (%) from the 15 CMIP3 models for the Northwest region. The lowest, 25th percentile, median, 75th percentile and highest values are given for the high (A2) and low (B1) emissions scenarios, and for each future time period (2021-2050, 2041-2070, and 2071-2099) with respect to the reference period of 1971-2000. Also shown are values from the distribution of the 9 NARCCAP models (NARCCAP) for 2041-2070, A2 only.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(225,5,'NARCCAP, SRES A2, PRECIPITATION CHANGE','Simulated difference in annual and seasonal mean precipitation (%) for the Northwest region, for 2041-2070 with respect to the reference period of 1971-2000. These projections are multi-model means from 9 NARCCAP regional climate simulations for the high (A2) emissions scenario. Note that the top and bottom color scales are unique, and different from that of Fig. 21. The simulated annual change is mostly upward, with drying seen in southwestern Oregon and central Idaho. Changes are mostly upward in winter, spring, and fall, and downward in summer. ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(226,5,'Model mean precipitation distribution summary (seasonal)','Distribution of the simulated seasonal mean change in precipitation (%) from the 15 CMIP3 models for the Northwest region. The lowest, 25th percentile, median, 75th percentile and highest values are given for the high (A2) and low (B1) emissions scenarios, and for the 2071-2099 time period with respect to the reference period of 1971-2000.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(227,5,'Model mean precipitation scatterplot (annual)','Simulated annual mean precipitation change (%) for the Northwest region, for each future time period (2021-2050, 2041-2070, and 2071-2099) with respect to the reference period of 1971-2000. Values are given for all 15 CMIP3 models for the high (SRESA2) and low (SRESB1) emissions scenarios. Also shown for 2041-2070 (high emissions scenario only) are values for the 9 NARCCAP models (NARCCAP), as well as for the 4 GCMs used to drive the NARCCAP simulations (NARCCAP_GCMs). The small plus signs indicate each individual model and the circles depict the multi-model means. The ranges of model-simulated changes are very large compared to the mean changes and to differences between the A2 and B1 scenarios. ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(228,5,'Model mean precipitation scatterplot (seasonal)','Simulated seasonal mean precipitation change (%) for the Northwest region, for each future time period (2021-2050, 2041-2070, and 2071-2099) with respect to the reference period of 1971-2000. Values are given for all 15 CMIP3 models for the high (A2) emissions scenario. Also shown are values for the 9 NARCCAP models (NARCCAP) for 2041-2070. The small plus signs indicate each individual model and the circles depict the multi-model means. Seasons are indicated as follows: winter (DJF, December-January-February), spring (MAM, March-April-May), summer (JJA, June-July-August), and fall (SON, September-October-November). The ranges of model-simulated changes are large compared to the mean changes and to differences between the seasons. ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(229,5,'NARCCAP, SRES A2, ANNUAL NUMBER OF DAYS PRECIPITATION > 1 INCH','Simulated percentage difference in the mean annual number of days with precipitation of greater than one inch for the Northwest region, for the 2041-2070 time period with respect to the reference period of 1980-2000 (top). Color only (category 1) indicates that less than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in the number of days. Color with stippling (category 3) indicates that more than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in the number of days, and more than 67% agree on the sign of the change (see text). Mean annual number of days with precipitation of greater than one inch for the 1980-2000 reference period (bottom left). Simulated mean annual number of days with precipitation of greater than one inch for the 2041-2070 future time period (bottom right). These fields are multi-model means from 8 NARCCAP regional climate simulations for the high (A2) emissions scenario. The models simulated increases over most of the region. ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(230,5,'NARCCAP, SRES A2, ANNUAL NUMBER OF DAYS PRECIPITATION > 0.3 INCH','Simulated percentage difference in the mean annual number of days with precipitation of greater than 0.3 inches for the Northwest region, for the 2041-2070 time period with respect to the reference period of 1980-2000 (top). Color only (category 1) indicates that less than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in the number of days. Color with stippling (category 3) indicates that more than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in the number of days, and more than 67% agree on the sign of the change (see text). Mean annual number of days with precipitation of greater than 0.3 inches for the 1980-2000 reference period (bottom left). Simulated mean annual number of days with precipitation of greater than 0.3 inches for the 2041-2070 future time period (bottom right). These fields are multi-model means from 8 NARCCAP regional climate simulations for the high (A2) emissions scenario. The models simulated increases for the central part of the region, with the greatest increases occurring in southeastern Oregon. There are simulated decreases in the southwestern part of the region and in central Idaho. ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(231,5,'NARCCAP, SRES A2, MAXIMUM CONSECUTIVE NUMBER OF DAYS PRECIP < 3MM','Simulated difference in the mean annual maximum number of consecutive days with precipitation of less than 0.1 inches/3 mm for the Northwest region, for the 2041-2070 time period with respect to the reference period of 1980-2000 (top). Color only (category 1) indicates that less than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in the number of consecutive days. Color with stippling (category 3) indicates that more than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in the number of consecutive days, and more than 67% agree on the sign of the change. Whited out areas (category 2) indicate that more than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in the number of consecutive days, but less than 67% agree of the sign of the change (see text). Mean annual maximum number of consecutive days with precipitation of less than 0.1 inches/3 mm for the 1980-2000 reference period (bottom left). Simulated mean annual maximum number of consecutive days with precipitation of less than 0.1 inches/3 mm for the 2041-2070 future time period (bottom right). These fields are multi-model means from 8 NARCCAP regional climate simulations for the high (A2) emissions scenario. The models simulate increases throughout the region, with the greatest increases occurring in western Oregon. ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(232,5,'NARCCAP summary statistics (precipitation)','Multi-model means and standard deviations of the simulated mean annual change in select precipitation variables from 9 NARCCAP simulations for the Northwest region. Multi-model means from the 11 Daily_CMIP3 simulations are also shown for comparison. Analyses are for the 2041-2070 time period with respect to the reference period of 1971-2000, for the high (A2) emissions scenario.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(233,5,'Observed decadal mean annual temperature change ','Observed decadal mean annual temperature change (deviations from the 1901-1960 average, °F) for the Northwest U.S. (black line). Based on a new gridded data set from NCDC for the NWS Cooperative Observer Network (R. Vose, personal communication, June 06, 2011). Gray lines indicate the 20th and 21st century simulations from 15 CMIP3 models, for the high (A2) emissions scenario. The observed rate of warming is within the envelope of model simulations.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(234,5,'Observed decadal mean seasonal temperature change','Observed decadal mean temperature change (deviations from the 1901-1960 average, °F) for the Northwest U.S. for winter (top left, blue line), spring (top right, green line), summer (bottom left red line), and fall (bottom right, orange line). Based on a new gridded data set from NCDC for the NWS Cooperative Observer Network (R. Vose, personal communication, June 06, 2011). Gray lines indicate 20th and 21st century simulations from 15 CMIP3 models, for the high (A2) emissions scenario. The observed amount of 20th century warming is generally within the envelope of model simulations.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(235,5,'Observed decadal mean annual precipitation change','Observed decadal mean annual precipitation change (deviations from the 1901-1960 average, %) for the Northwest U.S. (black line). Based on a new gridded data set from NCDC for the NWS Cooperative Observer Network (R. Vose, personal communication, June 06, 2011). Gray lines indicate the 20th and 21st century simulations from 15 CMIP3 models, for the high (A2) emissions scenario. Observed precipitation variations are within the model simulations.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(236,5,'Observed decadal mean seasonal precipitation change','Observed decadal mean precipitation change (deviations from the 1901-1960 average, %) for the Northwest U.S. for winter (top left, blue line), spring (top right, green line), summer (bottom left red line), and fall (bottom right, orange line). Based on a new gridded data set from NCDC for the NWS Cooperative Observer Network (R. Vose, personal communication, June 06, 2011). Gray lines indicate 20th and 21st century simulations from 15 CMIP3 models, for the high (A2) emissions scenario. Observed seasonal precipitation variations are within model simulations for all seasons.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(237,5,'Time series of mean annual temperature simulated vs observational','Time series of mean annual temperature for the Northwest region from observations (blue) and from all available CMIP3 global climate model simulations (black and grey). Black represents the mean and grey indicates the 5 and 95% limits of the model simulations. Model mean and percentile limits were calculated for each year separately and then smoothed. Results are shown for the low (B1) emissions scenario (left) and the high (A2) emissions scenario (right). A total of 74 simulations of the 20th century were used. For the 21st century, there were 40 simulations for the high emissions scenario and 32 for the low emissions scenario. For each model simulation, the annual temperature values were first transformed into anomalies by subtracting the simulation’s 1901-1960 average from each annual value. Then, the mean bias between model and observations was removed by adding the observed 1901-1960 average to each annual anomaly value from the simulation. For each year, all available model simulations were used to calculate the multi-model mean and the 5th and 95th percentile bounds for that year. Then, the mean and 5th and 95th percentile values were smoothed with a 5-year moving boxcar average.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(238,5,'Model temperature change scatterplot','Simulated decadal mean change in annual temperature (°F) for the Northwest U.S. for each future decadal time period (represented by their approximate midpoints, e.g. 2015 = 2011-2020), with respect to the reference period of 2001-2010. Values are given for all 15 CMIP3 models for the high (A2, top) and low (B1, bottom) emissions scenarios. Large circles depict the multi-model means. Each individual model is represented by a black plus sign (+), or a red x if the value is statistically significant at the 95% confidence level. Blue lines indicate the 10th and 90th percentiles of 30 annual anomaly values from 1981-2010. The model simulated warming by 2015 is not statistically significant but by mid-21st century, all models simulate statistically significant warming.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(239,5,'Model precipitation change scatterplot','Simulated decadal mean change in annual precipitation (%) for the Northwest U.S. for each future decadal time period (represented by their approximate midpoints, e.g. 2015 = 2011-2020), with respect to the reference period of 2001-2010. Values are given for all 15 CMIP3 models for the high (A2, top) and low (B1, bottom) emissions scenarios. Large circles depict the multi-model means. Each individual model is represented by a black plus sign (+), or a red x if the value is statistically significant at the 95% confidence level. Blue lines indicate the 10th and 90th percentiles of the 30 annual anomaly values from 1981-2010. Many models simulate precipitation changes that are not statistically significant out to the end of the 21st century.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(240,8,'Projected greenhouse gas emissions and atmospheric CO2 concentrations','a) Global greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions (GtCO2-equivalent per year) from 2000 to 2100 for two of the SRES scenarios: A2 (red line) and B1 (blue line). Adapted from IPCC (2007) Fig. 3.1. b) Observed annual mean (black line) and projected atmospheric CO2 concentrations (ppm) for two of the SRES scenarios: A2 (red line) and B1 (blue line). Observations are measurements from the Mauna Loa Observatory, Hawai‘i, from 1958 to 2008. Projections are from two fast carbon cycle models the Bern Model and the Integrated Science Assessment Model (ISAM). Data from IPCC (2012). These graphs show that the CO2 concentrations are comparable under these two scenarios in the early part of the 21st century but diverge greatly by the end of the century.','Greenhouse gas emissions, CO2 concentrations','1958-01-01 00:00:00','2100-12-31 00:00:00','90','-90','180','-180','Global	Observed, simulated	IPCC	Greenhouse gas emissions, CO2 concentrations',NULL,NULL,'2012-03-06 00:00:00'),(241,8,'Average annual temperature ','Average (1981-2010) annual temperature (°F) for the Great Plains region. Based on a new gridded version of COOP data from the National Climatic Data Center, the CDDv2 data set (R. Vose, personal communication, June 06, 2011). ',NULL,'1981-01-01 00:00:00','2010-12-31 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(242,8,'Average winter temperature','Average winter (December-February) temperature (°F), 1981-2010. Very cold temperatures of less than 15°F are observed in the far north while southern sections average in the 30s. These maps display general climate patterns. However, the gridded data set from which these maps were created does not have the necessary resolution to accurately represent the small-scale modifications to local near-shore climate conditions created by the temperature differential between the Great Lakes and the land. Therefore, climate conditions in the immediate vicinity of the lake shores may be different than what is displayed here.',NULL,'1981-12-01 00:00:00','2010-02-28 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(243,8,'Average annual precipitation','Average annual precipitation (inches), 1981-2010. Precipitation tends to increase from northwest to southeast, ranging from less than 20 inches in northwestern Minnesota to more than 45 inches in southern sections of Missouri, Illinois, and Indiana. These maps display general climate patterns. However, the gridded data set from which these maps were created does not have the necessary resolution to accurately represent the small-scale modifications to local near-shore climate conditions created by the temperature differential between the Great Lakes and the land. Therefore, climate conditions in the immediate vicinity of the lake shores may be different than what is displayed here.',NULL,'1981-01-01 00:00:00','2010-12-31 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(244,8,'Average summer precipitation','Average summer (June-August) precipitation (inches), 1981-2010. Precipitation is highest (more than 13 inches) in west-central sections, while less than 11 inches falls in extreme southern and northeastern sections. These maps display general climate patterns. However, the gridded data set from which these maps were created does not have the necessary resolution to accurately represent the small-scale modifications to local near-shore climate conditions created by the temperature differential between the Great Lakes and the land. Therefore, climate conditions in the immediate vicinity of the lake shores may be different than what is displayed here.',NULL,'1981-06-01 00:00:00','2010-08-31 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(245,8,'Average fall precipitation','Average fall (September-November) precipitation (inches), 1981-2010. Precipitation is lowest in the northwest (less than 6 inches) and increases to the south and east, with southern Missouri experiencing more than 12 inches. These maps display general climate patterns. However, the gridded data set from which these maps were created does not have the necessary resolution to accurately represent the small-scale modifications to local near-shore climate conditions created by the temperature differential between the Great Lakes and the land. Therefore, climate conditions in the immediate vicinity of the lake shores may be different than what is displayed here.',NULL,'1981-09-01 00:00:00','2010-11-30 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(246,8,'Average winter precipitation','Average winter (December-February) precipitation (inches), 1980/81-2009/10. Precipitation is lowest in the northwest (less than 2 inches) and increases to the south and east, with southern Missouri experiencing more than 12 inches.',NULL,'1980-12-01 00:00:00','2010-02-28 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(247,8,'Average spring precipitation','Average spring (March-May) precipitation (inches), 1981-2010. Precipitation is lowest in the northwest (less than 6 inches) and increases to the south and east, with southern Missouri experiencing more than 16 inches.',NULL,'1981-03-01 00:00:00','2010-05-31 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(248,8,'Average annual snowfall','Average annual snowfall (inches), 1981-2010. The stations where snowfall normals could be calculated are denoted by dots. Snowfall increases from south to north and is highest (more than 72 inches) in the lake-effect snow belts of the Michigan Upper Peninsula, western lower Michigan, and northeastern Ohio.',NULL,'1981-01-01 00:00:00','2010-12-31 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(249,8,'Average number of modified growing degree days','Average number of modified growing degree days (MGDD) determined from a base of 50°F to a ceiling of 86°F for the period of April-October 1981-2010.There is north to south increase, ranging from less than 2000 near Lake Superior to more than 4000 in far southern sections. These maps display general climate patterns. However, the gridded data set from which these maps were created does not have the necessary resolution to accurately represent the small-scale modifications to local near-shore climate conditions created by the temperature differential between the Great Lakes and the land. Therefore, climate conditions in the immediate vicinity of the lake shores may be different than what is displayed here.',NULL,'1981-04-01 00:00:00','2010-10-31 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(250,8,'Total Precipitation: Percent of Mean','Total precipitation expressed as the percentage of the long-term mean during the summer drought of 1988. Almost all areas experienced less than 75% of the long-term mean and some areas in Illinois, Iowa, Missouri, and Wisconsin received less than half of the long-term mean. These maps display general climate patterns. However, the gridded data set from which these maps were created does not have the necessary resolution to accurately represent the small-scale modifications to local near-shore climate conditions created by the temperature differential between the Great Lakes and the land. Therefore, climate conditions in the immediate vicinity of the lake shores may be different than what is displayed here.',NULL,'1988-04-01 00:00:00','1988-08-31 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(251,8,'Average annual number of snowstorms','Average annual number of snowstorms, defined as events producing 6 inches of snow or more in 24 hours or less, 1901-2001, (Changnon et al. 2006). A value of 0.5 indicates an average of 5 storms in 10 years. The number of storms increases from south to north and is locally highest in the lake-effect snowbelt to the south and west of Lakes Superior, Michigan, Huron, and Erie.',NULL,'1901-01-01 00:00:00','2001-12-31 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(252,8,'Annual average number of days with freezing rain','Annual average number of days with freezing rain, 1948-2000 (Changnon 2003).The maximum number occurs in the central Midwest from northern Missouri eastward to northern Ohio. ',NULL,'1948-01-01 00:00:00','2000-12-31 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(253,8,'Temporal distribution of snowstorm occurences','The temporal distribution of snowstorm (greater than 6 inches in 24 hours) occurrences for the Upper Midwest (a) and Lower Midwest (b) based on averages of all stations in each region and for each decade during 1901–2000, (Changnon et al. 2006). There has been in an upward trend in the northern Midwest and a downward trend in the southern Midwest.',NULL,'1901-01-01 00:00:00','2000-12-31 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(254,8,'Temperature Anomalies','Temperature anomaly (deviations from the 1901-1960 average, °F) for annual (black), winter (blue), spring (green), summer (red), and fall (orange), for the Midwest U.S. Based on data from the National Climatic Data Center for the NWS Cooperative Observer Network. The warmest periods were in the 1920s and 1930s and the 2000s.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(255,8,'Annual temperature anomalies for the Midwest ','Annual temperature anomalies for the Midwest from the CRUTEM3 data set. The anomalies are relative to 1961-1990. The data have a spatial resolution of 5 x 5°, thus the domain used to construct this figure is 35°N to 50°N and 95°W to 80°W. Also shown is a 5 year running mean and linear fits to the annual data for 1900-2010, 1950-2010 and 1979-2010. The shading represents the 95% confidence intervals on the fits. The slopes of the region-wide trend estimates are expressed in °C per decade and are shown for 3 time periods; 1900-2010, 1950-2010, and 1979-2010 (Pryor; Barthelmie 2012a). Data were downloaded from http://www.cru/uea.ac.uk/cru/data/temperature/#datdow. While trends for all periods are upward, the magnitude of the trend increases as the starting point for trend analysis becomes more recent.',NULL,'1895-01-01 00:00:00','2011-12-31 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(256,8,'Precipitation Anomalies','Precipitation anomaly (deviations from the 1901-1960 average, inches) for annual (black), winter (blue), spring (green), summer (red), and fall (orange), for the Midwest U.S. Based on data from the National Climatic Data Center for the NWS Cooperative Observer Network. Trends are only statistically significant annually and for the summer season.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(257,8,'1895-2011 trends in temperature anomaly and precipitation anomaly','1895-2011 trends in temperature anomaly (°F/decade) and precipitation anomaly (inches/decade) based on a new gridded version of the COOP data from the National Climatic Data Center (R. Vose, personal communication, June 06, 2011) for the Midwest U.S., for each season as well as the year as a whole. Only values statistically significant at the 95% confidence level are displayed. Statistical significance of trends was assessed using Kendall’s tau coefficient. The test using tau is a non-parametric hypothesis test.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(258,8,'Fraction of the mean annual total precipitation ','Fraction of the mean annual total precipitation from the top 10 wettest days in a year during 1971-2000. Only stations with 80 years of precipitation data between 1895 and 2002 are shown (Pryor et al. 2009b). The blue plus signs indicate stations where the top 10 wettest days make up a smaller amount of the annual precipitation while the black squares are stations where a larger fraction comes from the top 10 days. Based on data from the NWS Cooperative Observer Network. This indicates that the contribution of the top 10 days to annual precipitation increases from east to west',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(259,8,'Precipitation trends','a) Average precipitation per year during the top 10 wettest days (mm) (1971-2000). There is a general increase from north to south. b) Trend in sum of the top 10 wettest days in a year 1901-2000 expressed in a percent per decade. Red circle indicates the station showed a statistically significant increase through time; blue circle indicates a statistically significant decline. Plus symbol indicates trend was not significant (shown as 0 in the legend). The diameter of the dot scales linearly with trend magnitude (Pryor et al. 2009b). Most stations with statistically significance show upward trends. There are a number of stations whose trends are not statistically significant, which reflects the high spatial and temporal variability of heavy precipitation and possible data quality issues (see text). Only stations with 80 years of precipitation data between 1895 and 2002 are shown (Pryor et al. 2009b).',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(260,8,'Time series of extreme precipitation','Time series of extreme precipitation index for the occurrence of 1-day, 1 in 5 year extreme precipitation events, for the Midwest region. Based on data from the National Climatic Data Center for the NWS Cooperative Observer Network and updated from Kunkel et al. (2003). Only stations with less than 10% missing daily precipitation data for the period 1895-2010 are used in this analysis. Events are first identified for each individual station by ranking all daily precipitation values and choosing the top N/5 events, where N is the number of years of data for that particular station. Then, event numbers for each year are averaged for all stations in each 1x1° grid box. Finally, a regional average is determined by averaging the values for the individual grid boxes. This regional average is the extreme precipitation index. There is a statistically significant upward trend of 4%/decade.',NULL,'1895-01-01 00:00:00','2010-12-31 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(261,8,'Time series of cold waves','Time series of an index for the occurrence of cold waves defined as 4-day periods that are colder than the threshold for a 1 in 5 year recurrence, for the Midwest region. Based on data from the National Climatic Data Center for the NWS Cooperative Observer Network and updated from Kunkel et al. (1999). Only stations with less than 10% missing daily temperature data for the period 1895-2010 are used in this analysis. Events are first identified for each individual station by ranking all 4-day period mean temperature values and choosing the lowest non-overlapping N/5 events, where N is the number of years of data for that particular station. Then, event numbers for each year are averaged for all stations in each 1x1° grid box. Finally, a regional average is determined by averaging the values for the individual grid boxes. This regional average is the cold wave index. While there is no significant overall trend, the number of intense cold wave events has been very low during the last 10 years.',NULL,'1895-01-01 00:00:00','2010-12-31 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(262,8,'Time series of heat waves','Time series of an index for the occurrence of heat waves, defined as 4-day that are hotter than the threshold for a 1 in 5-year recurrence, for the Midwest region. Based on data from the National Climatic Data Center for the NWS Cooperative Observer Network and updated from Kunkel et al. (1999). Only stations with less than 10% missing daily temperature data for the period 1895-2010 are used in this analysis. Events are first identified for each individual station by ranking all 4-day period mean temperature values and choosing the highest non-overlapping N/5 events, where N is the number of years of data for that particular station. Then, event numbers for each year are averaged for all stations in each 1x1° grid box. Finally, a regional average is determined by averaging the values for the individual grid boxes. This regional average is the heat wave index. The most frequent intense heat waves occurred during the 1930s.',NULL,'1895-01-01 00:00:00','2010-12-31 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(263,8,'Mean annual wind speeds','Mean annual mean wind speeds for 1979-2000 (m s-1). Data are for a height of 10-m and are drawn from in situ observations in NCDC’s Integrated Surface Hourly (DS3505) data set (Pryor; Barthelmie 2012b). Average wind speeds are quite variable spatially, although there is a tendency for increases from east to west',NULL,'1979-01-01 00:00:00','2000-12-31 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(264,8,'Length of the growing season','Length of the growing season, defined as the period between the last occurrence of 32°F in the spring and first occurrence of 32°F in the fall. The red line is a 10-year moving average. Based on data from the National Climatic Data Center for the NWS Cooperative Observer Network and updated from Kunkel et al. (2004). Only stations with less than 10% missing daily temperature data for the period 1895-2010 are used in this analysis. Freeze events are first identified for each individual station. Then, event dates for each year are averaged for 1x1° grid boxes. Finally, a regional average is determined by averaging the values for the individual grid boxes. There has been a gradual increase since about 1980.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(265,8,'Snowfall trends','Snowfall trends for 1930-31 to 2006-07. Trends are given as a percentage of the 1937-38 to 2006-07 snowfall mean per year. Closed circles indicate positive trends while open circles are negative (Kunkel et al. 2009b). Based on data from the National Climatic Data Center for the NWS Cooperative Observer Network. Only stations with less than 10% missing daily snowfall data for the period 1930-2004 are used in this analysis. Furthermore, the stations shown here passed a stringent quality control analysis using expert judgment. The majority of stations exhibit downward trends. Upward trends tend to occur in northern regions and in Indiana.',NULL,'1930-01-01 00:00:00','2007-12-31 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(266,8,'Regional average annual percentages of homogeneous snowfall stations ','Regional average annual percentages of homogeneous snowfall stations (Kunkel et al. 2009c) exceeding the 90th percentile for the period of 1900-01 to 2006-07 for the 8 states. The snowfall percentile threshold for each station was calculated using the base period of 1937-38 to 2006-07. The percentage of stations exceeding the threshold for each region is calculated by dividing the number of stations in the region above the threshold by the number of active stations each year. The thick black line is an 11-year running mean of the percentages, and the dashed line is the number of active stations. Based on data from the National Climatic Data Center for the NWS Cooperative Observer Network. Only stations with less than 10% missing daily snowfall data for the period 1930-2004 are used in this analysis. Furthermore, the stations used here passed a stringent quality control analysis using expert judgment. Since 1985, the coverage of areas with snowfall exceeding the 90th percentile has been low.',NULL,'1901-01-01 00:00:00','2007-12-31 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(267,8,'Great Lakes hydrographs','Hydrographs of lake levels for each of the Great Lakes from 1860 to 2010. The linear trend of the lake level time series are shown by the straight black lines. Some fluctuations are noted across the lakes while other variability is specific to a particular lake. Data from the NOAA Great Lakes Environmental Research Laboratory. The trend for Michigan-Huron is downward and statistically significant.',NULL,'1860-01-01 00:00:00','2010-12-31 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(268,8,'Long-term change in ice-cover duration for Lake Mendota, WI','Long-term change in ice-cover duration for Lake Mendota, WI. The 10 coldest (?) and 10 warmest (?) extreme winters are indicated. From Magnuson (2010). There has been a consistent downward trend and 4 of the 10 shortest ice cover seasons occurred in the 1990s and 2000s.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(269,8,'Time series of annual averaged ice area for the Great Lakes','Time series of annual averaged ice area for the Great Lakes. From Wang et al. (2010).There has been a general downward trend over the last 30 years.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(270,8,'Average ice-out dates for Minnesota lakes','Average ice-out dates for Minnesota lakes. The number of lakes varies from 7 in the early part of the record to over 60 lakes in recent times. All values were normalized by applying an iterative process to form an average bias for each lake from a theoretical average lake for its location. Courtesy of J. Zandlo, Minnesota State Climatologist. Ice-out dates were latest in the mid-20th century through the 1970s. Since then, there has been a trend earlier ice-out dates.',NULL,'1895-01-01 00:00:00','2011-12-31 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(271,8,'Temperatures equal to or exceeding 70°F at 5 large Midwestern cities','Five-year running mean of the number of days with minimum temperatures equal to or exceeding 70°F at 5 large Midwestern cities: Chicago, IL (KMDW); Minneapolis, MN (KMSP); St Louis, MO (KSTL); Cleveland, OH (KCLE); and Columbus, OH (KCMK). For KCLE, temperature data started in 1938. All of the large cities exhibit statistically significant upward trends for the period of 1950-2009. Analysis performed at the Illinois State Water Survey.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(272,8,'The number of days with late afternoon dewpoint equal to or exceeding 70°F at Minneapolis-St. Paul','The number of days with late afternoon dewpoint equal to or exceeding 70°F at Minneapolis-St. Paul. Courtesy of J. Zandlo, Minnesota State Climatologist. Low values in the 1920s and 1930s are prominent.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(273,8,'CMIP3 Models Listing','Listing of the 15 models used for the CMIP3 simulations (left column). The 11 models used in the daily statistically-downscaled (Daily_CMIP3) analyses are indicated (right column). For detailed characteristics and documentation of the CMIP3 models, see:\rhttp://www-pcmdi.llnl.gov/ipcc/model_documentation/ipcc_model_documentation.php\r',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(274,8,'NARCCAP Models Listing','Combinations of the 4 GCMs and 6 RCMs that make up the 9 NARCCAP dynamically-downscaled model simulations. For detailed characteristics and documentation of the NARCCAP models, see:\rhttp://www.narccap.ucar.edu/data/model-info.html\r',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(275,8,'CMIP3, MULTI-MODEL MEAN SIMULATION Temperature Difference (F) from 1971-2000','Simulated difference in mean annual temperature (°F) for the Midwest region, for each future time period (2021-2050, 2041-2070, and 2071-2099) with respect to the reference period of 1971-2000. These fields are multi-model means from the 15 CMIP3 global climate simulations for the high (A2) and low (B1) emissions scenarios. Color with stippling (category 3) indicates that more than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in temperature, and more than 67% agree on the sign of the change (see text). Grid boxes whose centers are over the Great Lakes or outside the 8-state region are masked out. Temperature changes increase throughout the 21st century, more rapidly for the high emissions scenario.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(276,8,'NARCCAP, SRES A2, TEMPERATURE CHANGE','Simulated difference in mean annual and seasonal temperature (°F) for the Midwest region, for 2041-2070 with respect to the reference period of 1971-2000. These fields are multi-model means from 9 NARCCAP regional climate simulations for the high (A2) emissions scenario. Note that the color scale is different from that of Fig. 33. Grid boxes whose centers are over the Great Lakes or outside the 8-state region are masked out. Temperature changes for the NARCCAP simulations are similar to those for the CMIP3 global models (Fig. 33, middle left panel). Seasonal changes are similar, except slightly smaller in spring. ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(277,8,'Model mean temperature scatterplot (annual)','Simulated annual mean temperature change (°F) for the Midwest region, for each future time period (2021-2050, 2041-2070, and 2071-2099) with respect to the reference period of 1971-2000. Values are given for all 15 CMIP3 models for the high (SRESA2) and low (SRESB1) emissions scenarios. Also shown for 2041-2070 (high emissions scenario only) are values for the 9 NARCCAP models (NARCCAP), as well as for the 4 GCMs used to drive the NARCCAP simulations (NARCCAP_GCMs). The small plus signs indicate each individual model and the circles depict the multi-model means. The range of model-simulated changes is large compared to the mean differences between A2 and B1 in the early and middle 21st century. By the end of the 21st century, the difference between A2 and B1 is comparable to the range of B1 simulations.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(278,8,'Model mean temperature scatterplot (seasonal)','Simulated seasonal mean temperature change (°F) for the Midwest region, for each future time period (2021-2050, 2041-2070, and 2071-2099) with respect to the reference period of 1971-2000. Values are given for all 15 CMIP3 models for the high (A2) emissions scenario. The small plus signs indicate each individual model and the circles depict the multi-model means. Seasons are indicated as follows: winter (DJF, December-January-February), spring (MAM, March-April-May), summer (JJA, June-July-August), and fall (SON, September-October-November). The range of individual model-simulated changes is large compared to the differences among seasons and comparable to the differences between periods. ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(279,8,'Model mean temperature distribution summary (annual)','Distribution of the simulated annual mean change in temperature (°F) from the 15 CMIP3 models for the Midwest region. The lowest, 25th percentile, median, 75th percentile and highest values are given for the high (A2) and low (B1) emissions scenarios, and for each future time period (2021-2050, 2041-2070, and 2071-2099) with respect to the reference period of 1971-2000.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(280,8,'NARCCAP, SRES A2, ANNUAL NUMBER OF DAYS TMAX > 95F','Simulated difference in the mean annual number of days with a maximum temperature greater than 95°F (TMAX > 95F) for the Midwest region, for the 2041-2070 time period with respect to the reference period of 1980-2000 (top). Color only (category 1) indicates that less than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in the number of days. Color with stippling (category 3) indicates that more than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in the number of days, and more than 67% agree on the sign of the change (see text). Mean annual number of days with TMAX > 95F for the 1980-2000 reference period (bottom left). Simulated mean annual number of days with TMAX > 95F for the 2041-2070 future time period (bottom right). These fields are multi-model means from 8 NARCCAP regional climate simulations for the high (A2) emissions scenario. Grid boxes whose centers are over the Great Lakes or outside the 8-state region are masked out. The changes are upward everywhere. Increases are largest in the south and decrease northward, in a pattern similar to the present-day climatology. ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(281,8,'NARCCAP, SRES A2, ANNUAL NUMBER OF DAYS TMIN < 10F','Simulated difference in the mean annual number of days with a minimum temperature less than 10°F (TMIN < 10F) for the Midwest region, for the 2041-2070 time period with respect to the reference period of 1980-2000 (top). Color with stippling (category 3) indicates that more than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in the number of days, and more than 67% agree on the sign of the change (see text). Mean annual number of days with TMIN < 10F for the 1980-2000 reference period (bottom left). Simulated mean annual number of days with TMIN < 10F for the 2041-2070 future time period (bottom right). These fields are multi-model means from 8 NARCCAP regional climate simulations for the high (A2) emissions scenario. Grid boxes whose centers are over the Great Lakes or outside the 8-state region are masked out. Changes are downward everywhere. Decreases are largest in the north and become smaller southward, in a pattern similar to the present-day climatology. ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(282,8,'NARCCAP, SRES A2, ANNUAL NUMBER OF DAYS TMIN < 32F','Simulated difference in the mean annual number of days with a minimum temperature less than 32°F (TMIN < 32F) for the Midwest region, for the 2041-2070 time period with respect to the reference period of 1980-2000 (top). Color with stippling (category 3) indicates that more than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in the number of days, and more than 67% agree on the sign of the change (see text). Mean annual number of days with TMIN < 32F for the 1980-2000 reference period (bottom left). Simulated mean annual number of days with TMIN < 32F for the 2041-2070 future time period (bottom right). These fields are multi-model means from 8 NARCCAP regional climate simulations for the high (A2) emissions scenario. Grid boxes whose centers are over the Great Lakes or outside the 8-state region are masked out. Changes are downward everywhere. Decreases are largest in the east of the region and smallest in the northwest.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(283,8,'NARCCAP, SRES A2, ANNUAL MAXIMUM NUMBER OF CONSECUTIVE DAYS TMAX > 95','Simulated difference in the mean annual maximum number of consecutive days with a maximum temperature greater than 95°F (TMAX > 95F) for the Midwest region, for the 2041-2070 time period with respect to the reference period of 1980-2000 (top). Color with stippling (category 3) indicates that more than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in the number of consecutive days, and more than 67% agree on the sign of the change (see text). Mean annual maximum number of consecutive days with TMAX > 95F for the 1980-2000 reference period (bottom left). Simulated mean annual maximum number of consecutive days with TMAX > 95F for the 2041-2070 future time period (bottom right). These fields are multi-model means from 8 NARCCAP regional climate simulations for the high (A2) emissions scenario. Grid boxes whose centers are over the Great Lakes or outside the 8-state region are masked out. The changes are upward everywhere. Increases are largest in the south and decrease northward, in a pattern similar to the present-day climatology.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(284,8,'NARCCAP summary statistics (temperature)','Multi-model means and standard deviations of the simulated annual mean change in select temperature variables from 9 NARCCAP simulations for the Midwest region. Multi-model means from the 11 Daily_CMIP3 simulations are also shown for comparison. Analyses are for the 2041-2070 time period with respect to the reference period of 1971-2000, for the high (A2) emissions scenario.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(285,8,'NARCCAP, SRES A2, LENGTH OF FROST-FREE SEASON','Simulated difference in the mean annual length of the frost-free season for the Midwest region, for the 2041-2070 time period with respect to the reference period of 1980-2000 (top). Color with stippling (category 3) indicates that more than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in the length of the frost-free season, and more than 67% agree on the sign of the change (see text). Mean annual length of the frost-free season for the 1980-2000 reference period (bottom left). Simulated mean annual length of the frost-free season for the 2041-2070 future time period (bottom right). These fields are multi-model means from 8 NARCCAP regional climate simulations for the high (A2) emissions scenario. Grid boxes whose centers are over the Great Lakes or outside the 8-state region are masked out. The frost-freeze season is simulated to become longer throughout the region, with increases mostly in the 20-30 day range.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(286,8,'NARCCAP, SRES A2, ANNUAL TOTAL COOLING DEGREE DAYS','Simulated difference in the mean annual number of cooling degree days for the Midwest region, for the 2041-2070 time period with respect to the reference period of 1980-2000 (top). Color with stippling (category 3) indicates that more than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in the number of cooling degree days, and more than 67% agree on the sign of the change (see text). Mean annual number of cooling degree days for the 1980-2000 reference period (bottom left). Simulated mean annual number of cooling degree days for the 2041-2070 future time period (bottom right). These fields are multi-model means from 8 NARCCAP regional climate simulations for the high (A2) emissions scenario. Grid boxes whose centers are over the Great Lakes or outside the 8-state region are masked out. There are increases everywhere with the increases becoming larger from north to south. ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(287,8,'NARCCAP, SRES A2, ANNUAL TOTAL HEATING DEGREE DAYS','Simulated difference in the mean annual number of heating degree days for the Midwest region, for the 2041-2070 time period with respect to the reference period of 1980-2000 (top). Color with stippling (category 3) indicates that more than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in the number of heating degree days, and more than 67% agree on the sign of the change (see text). Mean annual number of heating degree days for the 1980-2000 reference period (bottom left). Simulated mean annual number of heating degree days for the 2041-2070 future time period (bottom right). These fields are multi-model means from 8 NARCCAP regional climate simulations for the high (A2) emissions scenario. Grid boxes whose centers are over the Great Lakes or outside the 8-state region are masked out. There are decreases everywhere with the largest decreases in the north.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(288,8,'Model mean precipitation distribution summary (annual)','Distribution of the simulated annual mean change in precipitation (%) from the 15 CMIP3 models for the Midwest region. The lowest, 25th percentile, median, 75th percentile and highest values are given for the high (A2) and low (B1) emissions scenarios, and for each future time period (2021-2050, 2041-2070, and 2071-2099) with respect to the reference period of 1971-2000. Also shown are values from the distribution of the 9 NARCCAP models (NARCCAP) for 2041-2070, A2 only.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(289,8,'CMIP3, MULTI-MODEL MEAN SIMULATION Precipitation Difference (%) from 1971-2000','Simulated difference in mean annual precipitation (%) for the Midwest region, for each future time period (2021-2050, 2041-2070, and 2071-2099) with respect to the reference period of 1971-2000. These projections are multi-model means from the 15 CMIP3 global climate simulations for the high (A2) and low (B1) emissions scenarios. Color only (category 1) indicates that less than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in precipitation. Color with stippling (category 3) indicates that more than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in precipitation, and more than 67% agree on the sign of the change. Whited out areas (category 2) indicate that more than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in precipitation, but less than 67% agree of the sign of the change (see text). Grid boxes whose centers are over the Great Lakes or outside the 8-state region are masked out. Generally, the models simulate increases in the north and east and little change or decreases in the southwest part of the region. ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(290,8,'Model mean precipitation distribution summary (seasonal)','Distribution of the simulated seasonal mean change in precipitation (%) from the 15 CMIP3 models for the Midwest region. The lowest, 25th percentile, median, 75th percentile and highest values are given for the high (A2) and low (B1) emissions scenarios, and for the 2071-2099 time period with respect to the reference period of 1971-2000.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(291,8,'NARCCAP, SRES A2, PRECIPITATION CHANGE','Simulated difference in mean annual and seasonal precipitation (%) for the Midwest region, for 2041-2070 with respect to the reference period of 1971-2000. These projections are multi-model means from 9 NARCCAP regional climate simulations for the high (A2) emissions scenario. Note that the top and bottom color scales are unique, and different from that of Fig. 44. Grid boxes whose centers are over the Great Lakes or outside the 8-state region are masked out. The annual change is near zero in the south and an increase of 5-10% in much of the north. Changes are mostly upward in the winter, spring, and fall, and downward in summer in the south. ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(292,8,'Model mean precipitation scatterplot (annual)','Simulated annual mean precipitation change (%) for the Midwest region, for each future time period (2021-2050, 2041-2070, and 2071-2099) with respect to the reference period of 1971-2000. Values are given for all 15 CMIP3 models for the high (SRESA2) and low (SRESB1) emissions scenarios. Also shown for 2041-2070 (high emissions scenario only) are values for the 9 NARCCAP models (NARCCAP), as well as for the 4 GCMs used to drive the NARCCAP simulations (NARCCAP_GCMs). The small plus signs indicate each individual model and the circles depict the multi-model means. The ranges of model-simulated changes are very large compared to the mean changes and to differences between the A2 and B1 scenarios. ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(293,8,'Model mean precipitation scatterplot (seasonal)','Simulated seasonal mean precipitation change (%) for the Midwest region, for each future time period (2021-2050, 2041-2070, and 2071-2099) with respect to the reference period of 1971-2000. Values are given for all 15 CMIP3 models for the high (A2) emissions scenario. Also shown are values for the 9 NARCCAP models (NARCCAP) for 2041-2070. The small plus signs indicate each individual model and the circles depict the multi-model means. Seasons are indicated as follows: winter (DJF, December-January-February), spring (MAM, March-April-May), summer (JJA, June-July-August), and fall (SON, September-October-November). The ranges of model-simulated changes are large compared to the mean changes and to differences between the seasons. ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(294,8,'NARCCAP, SRES A2, ANNUAL NUMBER OF DAYS PRECIPITATION > 1 INCH','Simulated percentage difference in the mean annual number of days with precipitation of greater than 1 inch for the Midwest region, 