mperatures at 1-meter depth for 2000-09, 2040-49, and 2090-99. Fields are from GIPL permafrost model simulations driven by downscaled CMIP3 climate model output for the B1 (top panels) and A2 (bottom panels) scenarios. As indicated by color bars, blue shades represent temperatures below 0°C and red shades represent temperatures above 0°C. Figure provided by S. Marchenko and the Geophysical Institute Permafrost Laboratory, University of Alaska, Fairbanks.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(383,9,'Sea ice area Bering Sea / E. Siberia-Chukchi','Winter (March-April average) sea ice area (106 km2) in the Bering Sea, and summer (August- September average) sea ice area in the East Siberia-Chukchi Seas from 1900 to 2100, as simulated by different CMIP3 models (thin colored lines). The thick blue line is a multi-model mean, and the thick red line shows recent observational data (from Overland; Wang 2007).',NULL,'1900-01-01 00:00:00','2100-12-31 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(384,6,'Projected greenhouse gas emissions and atmospheric CO2 concentrations','a) Global greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions (GtCO2-equivalent per year) from 2000 to 2100 for two of the SRES scenarios: A2 (red line) and B1 (blue line). Adapted from IPCC (2007) Fig. 3.1. b) Observed annual mean (black line) and projected atmospheric CO2 concentrations (ppm) for two of the SRES scenarios: A2 (red line) and B1 (blue line). Observations are measurements from the Mauna Loa Observatory, Hawai‘i, from 1958 to 2008. Projections are from two fast carbon cycle models the Bern Model and the Integrated Science Assessment Model (ISAM). Data from IPCC (2012). These graphs show that the CO2 concentrations are comparable under these two scenarios in the early part of the 21st century but diverge greatly by the end of the century.','Greenhouse gas emissions, CO2 concentrations','1958-01-01 00:00:00','2100-12-31 00:00:00','90','-90','180','-180','Global	Observed, simulated	IPCC	Greenhouse gas emissions, CO2 concentrations',NULL,NULL,'2012-03-06 00:00:00'),(385,6,'Annual average surface temperature anomalies','Annual average surface temperature anomalies are increasing at both high and low-elevation stations in Hawai‘i (a total of 21). Temperature anomalies are calculated first as the departure from the monthly mean, and then averaged into a calendar year. Anomalies greater than zero indicate temperatures that are above-average, while anomalies less than zero indicate below-average temperatures. A 7-year running-mean filter has been applied to the data to create a smoothed trend curve (black curve). Linear trends have been computed for two periods, 1919-2006 and 1975-2006, where the latter period emphasizes the observed enhanced warming. The steeper warming trend in high-elevation stations (>800 meters/0.5 mile) is visible in the bottom panel, especially when compared to that of the low-elevation stations in the middle panel (<800 meters/0.5 mile). Error bars show a standard deviation range of +/-0.5. Thick lines show 7-year running means. Asterisks indicate slopes significant at p = 0.05. (Giambelluca et al. 2008).',NULL,'1919-01-01 00:00:00','2006-12-31 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(386,6,'Air temperature trends','Air Temperature in Hawai‘i (red line) prior to 1975 is tightly coupled to the Pacific Decadal Oscillation (PDO) (blue line) (top panel). Since 1975, air temperature has diverged increasingly from the observed PDO, which may indicate the increasing influence of climate change in the North Central Pacific subregion. Local sea surface temperature anomalies (blue line, for 22°N, 156°W based on the Smith and Reynolds (2004) Extended Reconstructed Sea Surface Temperatures (ERSST) data set) are also coupled to air temperatures (red line) in Hawai‘i (bottom panel), and show a similar decoupling around 1975 (Giambelluca et al. 2008).',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(387,6,'Trade-Wind Inversion Occurence','The frequency of occurrence of the trade-wind inversion over Hawai‘i Island increased during the 1990s from less than 80% to occurring around 90% of the time. This finding is consistent with current observations of reduced precipitation, especially for the high-elevations in Hawai‘i (Cao et al. 2007).',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(388,6,'Time series of Hawaii Rainfall Index','The annual time series of the Hawai‘i Rainfall Index (HRI) from 1905 to 2010 shows a long-term downward (drying) trend over the last 105 years. Annual values (July to June) are used. For example, 2010 refers to the period from July 2010 to June 2011. Nine stations from each of three islands (Kaua‘i, O‘ahu, and Hawai‘i) are selected. These 27 stations are representative of the spatial variability of rainfall with regard to the direction of the prevailing northeast trade winds (i.e., windward and leeward) and to varying elevation levels (i.e., high and low). A normalization method is applied to each station to obtain standardized anomalies and the HRI is then calculated as the average of all station anomalies from three islands (Chu and Chen 2005).',NULL,'1905-01-01 00:00:00','2010-12-31 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(389,6,'Precipitation anomaly trends','In trends similar to air temperature, precipitation anomalies have followed the same pattern of decoupling from the Pacific Decadal Oscillation (PDO) since 1975, most likely as a result of long-term average climate change. Precipitation anomalies at stations on four Hawaiian Islands in the wet season (November – April) that are smoothed decadally correspond to the decadally smoothed PDO index. Anomalies greater than zero indicate precipitation that is above-average, while anomalies less than zero indicate below-average precipitation (Frazier et al. 2011).',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(390,6,'Time series of tropical cyclones','Time series of tropical cyclones (tropical storms and hurricanes) in the Central North Pacific basin from 1966 to 2010. Although there was a period of greater tropical cyclone activity from the 1980s to mid-1990s, the basin has again entered a quieter time, with fewer average annual occurrences of storms. Broken lines denote the means for the periods 1966-81, 1982-94, and 1995-2010 (Chu 2002).',NULL,'1966-01-01 00:00:00','2010-12-31 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(391,6,'Drought trends','All four major Hawaiian Islands (O‘ahu, Kaua‘i, Maui and Hawai‘i Island) have experienced increasing winter drought since the 1950s, defined by a longer annual maximum number of consecutive dry days. Upward (downward) triangles denote the increasing (decreasing) direction of drought trends. Black (gray) triangles indicate trends significant at the 5% (10%) level (Chu et al. 2010).',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(392,6,'Maximum Temperature Anomaly in West Micronesia','Maximum monthly temperature anomaly time series from 1952 to 2012 for single monitoring stations with the most data in Yap, Guam, and Palau. The Northern Hemisphere temperature time series (purple line, Hadley CRU NH) is superimposed for comparison. Trends in maximum temperatures in the Western region of the Western North Pacific subregion appear to be increasing at the same general rate as average Northern Hemisphere temperatures (Lander and Guard 2003).',NULL,'1952-01-01 00:00:00','2012-12-31 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(393,6,'Maximum Temperature Anomaly in East Micronesia','Maximum monthly temperature anomaly time series from 1952 to 2012 for single monitoring stations with the most data in Kwajalein and Majuro in the RMI. The Northern Hemisphere temperature time series (purple line, Hadley CRU NH) is superimposed for comparison. Trends in maximum temperatures in the Eastern region of the Western North Pacific subregion have high-levels of variability, and may reflect issues in the quality of the data or station infrastructure.',NULL,'1952-01-01 00:00:00','2012-12-31 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(394,6,'Annual rainfall per island (Western North Pacific subregion)','Annual rainfall (inches per month per decade) in the Western North Pacific subregion from 1950 to 2010 show that while islands in the West are tending towards getting slightly more precipitation, islands in the East are experiencing larger magnitudes of less precipitation. Blue shading indicates wetter, and orange shading indicates drier. The size of the dot is proportional to the magnitude of the trend as per inset scale.',NULL,'1950-01-01 00:00:00','2010-12-31 00:00:00',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(395,6,'CMIP3, MULTI-MODEL MEAN SIMULATION Temperature Difference (F) from 1971-1999','Simulated difference in mean annual temperature (°F) for Hawai‘i, for each future time period (2021-2050, 2041-2070, and 2070-2099) with respect to the reference period of 1971-1999. These fields are multi-model means for the high (A2) and low (B1) emissions scenarios from the 14 (B1) or 15 (A2) CMIP3 global climate simulations. Color with hatching (category 3) indicates that more than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in temperature, and more than 67% agree on the sign of the change (see text).',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(396,6,'CMIP3, MULTI-MODEL MEAN SIMULATION Precipitation Difference (%) from 1971-1999','Simulated difference in mean annual precipitation (%) for Hawai‘i, for each future time period (2021-2050, 2041-2070, and 2070-2099) with respect to the reference period of 1971-1999. These fields are multi-model means for the high (A2) and low (B1) emissions scenarios from the 14 (B1) or 15 (A2) CMIP3 global climate simulations. Color only (category 1) indicates that less than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in precipitation. Whited out areas (category 2) indicate that more than 50% of the models show a statistically significant change in precipitation, but less than 67% agree of the sign of the change (see text).',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(397,6,'CMIP5 climate change results','CMIP5 climate change results from the Hadley Centre HADGEM2-ES model. Shown are the mean annual cycles of precipitation averaged over 5 individual boxes corresponding to the locations of the major groups of US-API. Results for late 20th century from the CMIP5 “Historical” simulation (black curves) and for late 21st century from a RCP4.5 climate change projection simulation (red curves). Each curve represents results from 20 years of simulation. Results are from four 20th century ensemble members and from a single RCP4.5 realization. The red numbers indicate the percentage change of annual mean precipitation in the RCP4.5 results relative to the late 20th century simulations.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(398,6,'Monthly rainfall over the main Hawaiian Islands','Monthly rainfall over the main Hawaiian Islands from a one-year simulation with the regional WRF-ARW model, as described in Zhang et al. (2012). Results from two versions of the model are shown in the middle and lower rows. Observations in the top row are objective analyses based on rain gauge observations at a large number of stations. Results for November 2005, March 2006, and August 2006 are shown.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(399,6,'Analysis of the simulated Sea Surface Temperature','Analysis of the simulated SST in the tropical Pacific in the late 21st century relative to that in the late 20th century in 16 global climate models. Changes in the amplitude of ENSO cyclic variations are plotted on the vertical axis, and a measure of changes in the mean SST gradients are indicated on the horizontal axis. The models show no pattern of agreement even on the sign of the change in strength of future ENSO oscillations, but most of 